{Hello, dear readers! Welcome to this lecture on the recent opening trends in
the London System with 2...g6. In this PGN file, I have presented my comments
and analysis based on recent games. I have also given reference games in
different variations so that you can refer to them quickly whenever needed. I
hope you will learn and enjoy this PGN file! All the Best :)} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 O-O 5. Be2 d6 {is the main way for Black to play here. By
keeping the pawn on d6 he keeps his options flexible.} (5... c5 {does not
carry an independent value as after,} 6. O-O {Black should transpose to
typical ways of handling this position by playing moves like 6... d6 or 6...b6
or 6...d5.} Qb6 {Going after the b2 pawn immediately with does not work well
due to,} 7. Nc3 $1 Qxb2 8. Nb5) (5... d5 {Black generally does not advance his
d-pawn two squares as 5...d5 is a bit committal. This position usually arises
when Black has already played ...d5 on the 1st or 2nd move.} 6. O-O c5 {
GM Dreev has successfully employed this way of playing from Black side in a
few recent online games.}) 6. O-O {Now Black has essentially two ways to play
in this position. 1. Break in the centre with ...e5 and 2. Break in the centre
with ...c5. Black has different moves possible here but all moves are aimed at
breaking with ...e5 and ...c5 immediately or after a few moves.} (6. h3 {
is also a possible move order, but it is ideal to play h2-h3 when Black
prepares to ...e5.} c5 {was a recent try by Ding against Carlsen.} 7. O-O {
this is the best move according to me. The point is that Black's idea of} (7.
c3 {has also been played for quite a while. Black exchanges queen with,} Qb6 8.
Qb3 Be6 $1 {Forcing White to exchange on b6.} 9. Qxb6 axb6 {[%csl Ra2]} 10. a3
{[#]} Bd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5c6] this is an important manoeuver of the bishop. Black
would like to place his bishop on c6 covering the h1-a8 diagonal. From c6 the
bishop also supports queenside pawn advance with ...b5.} 11. Nbd2 Bc6 12. O-O
Nbd7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (24) Grachev,B (2612)-Chigaev,M (2588) chess.com INT 2020}) (
7. Nbd2 $6 {This was the choice of Carlsen but it is inferior as it allows
Black to prepare a quick ...e5 break.} cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6 9. c3 {[#]} (9. Bh2 {
can be met by,} Re8 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 10. Nc4 {[%csl Ge5]} Nd5 {[%cal Ge7e5]
again aiming for ...e5. Also, the knight is very stable on the d5 square.} 11.
O-O e5 $11 {With this pawn advance Black gains a comfortable position. 0-1 (59)
Shagbazyan,T (2412)-Pantsulaia,L (2603) Tbilisi GEO 2019}) 9... e5 $1 {using
tactics to break with quickly with ...e5.} 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bg5 (11. Nxe5 {
is met by,} Re8 {[%csl Re5]} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. O-O Nd5 $1 14. Bg3 {[#]} Bxc3 $1
$15 {The key idea that gives Black a slight edge due to his active pieces.})
11... h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 {Black has gained the double bishops and should be
preferred in this position.} 13. O-O Rd8 14. Qb3 Qe7 15. Rad1 e4 $1 {[%cal
Re4f3,Re4e3]} 16. Nh2 e3 17. Ndf3 exf2+ 18. Rxf2 Be6 $36 {and it is clear that
Black has the initiative here because of the bishop pair and slightly exposed
White Kingside. ½-½ (41) Carlsen,M (2863)-Ding Liren (2791) chess24.com INT
2020}) 7... Qb6 {can be strongly met with,} 8. Nbd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4] White
ignores the threat to the b2 pawn and prepares to bring his knight on c4.} Be6
{[%csl Gc4] covering the c4 square can be met by,} (8... Qxb2 $2 {ofcourse
does not work due to,} 9. Nc4 Qb5 (9... Qc3 $4 10. Rb1 $18 {[%cal Rb1b3]}) 10.
Nxd6 $16) 9. Ng5 Bd7 10. Nc4 {When White pushes Black's pieces back. I
slightly prefer White in this position: 1-0 (40) Illingworth, M (2493)-Preotu,
R (2487) chess.com INT 2020}) 6... Nbd7 {by placing his knight on d7 Black
keeps his options open to ...e5 or ...b6.} (6... Nc6 {with this development of
the knight, Black makes it clear that he wants to break with ...e5 quickly. 6..
. Nfd7 is the same as 6...Nc6. Black needs to play both these knight moves to
carry out the ...e5 break.} 7. h3 {A typical prophylactic move, vacating the
h2 square for the bishop.} (7. Nc3 Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5]} (7... Nh5 $5 {is a
decent try as well.} 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Nd2 Nf4 $146 11. exf4 gxh4 12. Nf3
{[%csl Gd4,Rh4]} e6 {[%cal Gd8h4]} 13. g3 e5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gc8h3] Black opens
up the position as White's light squares are weak.}) 8. d5 Nce5 9. Nd4 (9. Nxe5
Nxe5 10. e4 {[%cal Gd1d2] was a better way for White to continue.}) 9... c5 $1
10. dxc6 $6 {this opens the b-file which Black can use to create pressure on
the queenside.} (10. Nb3 f5 $11 {[%cal Ge5f7,Gd7f6]}) 10... bxc6 11. Bg3 $6 c5
12. Nb3 Nb6 $15 {[%cal Ge5c4,Gb6c4] and Black was pressing in the game ½-½ 
(104) Fedoseev,V (2678)-Bazeev,G (2401) chess.com INT 2020}) (7. c3 {is a
solid move that was chosen by GM Artemiev in a recent game. By c3 White makes
sure that Black does not get to play ...e5 immediately.} Nd7 8. h3 e5 9. Bh2 f5
{a typical follow up to ...e5.} 10. Na3 Kh8 {a nice useful move getting away
from the a2-g8 diagonal.} 11. dxe5 Ndxe5 12. Nb5 Bd7 13. Nbd4 Qf6 $11 {and
Black was doing fine in the game (45) Artemiev, V (2711)-Pavlidis, A (2536)
chess.com INT 2020}) 7... Nd7 {This is the reason why Black developed his
knight on c6 so that the d7 square is free for the f6-knight. Black blocks his
c8-bishop temporarily but prepares a quick ...e5 break. Another benefit of
moving the knight from f6 is that Black can gain more space on the Kingside
with ...f5.} (7... e5 $1 {is the correct way to play here. Black uses tactics 
(again) to break in the centre straight away.} 8. dxe5 Ne4 {[%csl Rb2] this is
the point. The b2-pawn hangs.} 9. Bh2 (9. Qd5 $2 dxe5 10. Qxe4 exf4 $17 {
[%cal Gf4e3,Gg7b2]}) 9... dxe5 $11 {The position is more or less equal but
Black won a nice game. 0-1 (39) Pakleza,Z (2506)-Kanarek,M (2535) Poland 2016})
8. Bh2 e5 9. c4 {This is White's usual response to Black's central aggression.
With 9.c4 White gains space and is ready to create pressure on the queenside
in case Black opts for closing the centre with ...e4.} (9. dxe5 $6 {In general
I prefer not to exchange on e5 from the White side as now Black's g7 bishop
gets opened and starts putting pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal. Also after 9.
dxe5 White will find it tough to create any pressure on the queenside.} dxe5
10. Nc3 f5 11. Bc4+ Kh8 12. a3 e4 $15 {Firouzja went on to win a nice
attacking game. 0-1 (48) Sengupta,D (2527)-Firouzja,A (2728) chess.com INT 2020
}) 9... f5 {this pawn advance is a logical follow-up to 8...e5.} (9... exd4 $6
{is objectively not the best try for Black but it leads to interesting
possibilities.} 10. exd4 Qf6 (10... Re8 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gf6e4] Black covers the
e-file and intends to fight for the e4 square by bringing his knight to f6
next.} 11. Nc3 Nf6 12. d5 {this gains space for White but opens up the a1-h8
diagonal for Black's bishop, so White needs to be careful.} (12. Bd3 {this
seems to be the simplest, not only covering the e4-square but also preventing.
..Bf5.} d5 $146 {is a possible try to fight for the e4-square. But White has,}
(12... Nh5 13. Bc2 Nb4 14. Ba4 $16 {was clearly better for White as Black's
pieces are uncoordinated.0-1 (36) Grachev,B (2654)-Aronian,L (2801) Moscow 2010
}) 13. c5 Ne4 {and now White gains the initiative forcibly with,} 14. Nb5 $1 {
[%csl Rc7]} Re7 15. Bxe4 $1 dxe4 16. d5 $36) 12... Nb4 13. a3 Na6 14. b4 $1 {
A strong move that works well for White tactically. White prevents Na6-c5.} (
14. Bd3 $6 {was recently played by Piesik against Gajewski but Black gained
easy equality by bringing his knight into the game with,} Nc5 15. Bc2 Nfe4 $11
{0-1 (39) Piesik,P (2409)-Gajewski,G (2613) Katowice POL 2019}) 14... Ng4 {
[%csl Rc3] an obvious move hitting the unprotected knight on c3.} 15. hxg4 Bxc3
16. Rc1 Bb2 17. Rb1 Bxa3 $6 {this is the most tempting move but falls short
for Black unfortunately.} (17... Bg7 18. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gc4c5] The
Black knight on a6 is misplaced and White has ideas to break on the queenside
with c4-c5.}) 18. c5 $1 dxc5 (18... Bxb4 19. Bxa6 Bxc5 20. Bxb7 Bxb7 21. Rxb7
Bb6 {it seems that Black has managed to gain some grounds by trapping the
White rook on b7, but White gets strong attacking chances after,} 22. Bf4 Qc8
23. Rxb6 axb6 24. Nh2 $18 {[%csl Rf6,Gg4,Rg7,Rh6] and the dark squares around
the Black King are too weak.}) 19. b5 Nb4 (19... Nb8 {[%cal Gc5c4]} 20. Bc4 $18
{[%csl Ra3] this simple prophylactic move preventing ...c4 gives White a
winning advantage. Black's dark square bishop has abandoned his King and Black
is going to suffer on the Kingside.}) 20. Rb3 {[%cal Rb3a3]} Qxd5 (20... Bc1
21. Bc4 Bh6 22. Ne5 $18 {[%cal Rb3f3,Rd5d6] with a crushing attack!}) 21. Rxa3
Qxd1 22. Bxd1 $16 {White has better chances in this endgame as Black's
queenside is not ideal.}) 11. Nc3 $1 {a key move for White that gives him a
slight edge.} (11. d5 $6 {gives Black easy play after,} Nd4 $1 (11... Qxb2 12.
dxc6 Qxa1 13. cxd7 Bxd7 14. Qb3 $13 {leads to unclear play due to material
imbalance.}) 12. Nc3 a6 {[%csl Gb5] a nice prophylactic move covering the b5
square.} 13. Qxd4 Qxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Rac1 Re8 $15 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd7c5]
Black is slightly better as we have good squares for our pieces and the
d4-bishop exerts pressure on White's Position.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13.
Nd5 $1 {[%cal Rd5c7] This is the point! With an attack on c7 White regains his
pawn.} c6 (13... Qxb2 $2 14. Rb1 Qxa2 15. Nxc7 {[%cal Rh2d6] and Black loses
material.} Nc5 16. Nxa8 Bf5 17. Rb5 $18 {1/2-1/2 (56) Prie,E (2490)-Moussard,J
(2426) Caen 2011}) 14. Ne7+ Kh8 15. Bxd6 Re8 (15... Qxb2 $5 {is greedy but
seems to work for Black.} 16. Rb1 Qxa2 17. Re1 Nf6 18. Bf3 $146 (18. Be5 {
0-1 (40) Prie,E (2491)-Bedouin,X (2378) Nimes 2009}) 18... Qxc4 {This leads to
an interesting variation where Black holds but not without difficulties.} (
18... Rd8 19. c5 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gd6,Ge7] Black is under pressure due to
White's active pieces.}) 19. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 20. Rc1 Qh4 $8 {it is essential to
keep the queen near Black's King.} 21. Bxf8 Bxf8 22. Rxc6 {[%cal Rc6f6,Rf3a8]}
(22. Bxc6 $2 Rb8 $19 {[%cal Rc8h3] Black just enjoys extra material.}) 22...
Bb7 ({There is no time for,} 22... Rb8 $2 23. Qd8 $16 {[%cal Rc6c8,Rd8f6]
White wins a piece.}) 23. Rc7 Bxf3 24. Qxf3 {[%csl Ra8]} Rb8 25. Rxf7 Bg7 26.
Ree7 Rg8 27. Qb7 Qd4 $1 {With this resource Black holds the game.} 28. Rxg7
Rxg7 29. Rxg7 Qa1+ 30. Kh2 Qe5+ 31. g3 Ng4+ 32. hxg4 Qxg7 33. Qb8+ Qg8 34. Qxa7
h6 $11 {and I believe Black can easily hold this queen endgame.}) 16. Bg4 {
[%cal Re7c8,Rg4d7] this leads to a slightly pleasant endgame for White after,}
Nb6 17. Nxc8 Nxc8 18. Qxd4 Bxd4 19. Ba3 $14 {White retains a slight edge due
to the bishop pair. ½-½ (54) Ponizil,C (2469)-Rasik,V (2446) Czech Republic
2016}) 10. Nc3 Kh8 $5 {[%csl Gh8] This is was the choice of Stockfish in a
recent game. It is useful to tuck our King on h8 as the a2-g8 diagonal is
always vulnerable once we play ...f5.} ({The Aggressive,} 10... g5 $6 11. dxe5
(11. d5 {kicking the Black knight back to b8.} Ncb8 {and now,} 12. g4 $1 $146 {
is slightly odd but a nice strategic solution taking control of the light
squares on the Kingside.}) 11... dxe5 (11... Ndxe5 $6 {is inferior due to,} 12.
c5 $1 {a timely pawn break opening up the position.} dxc5 13. Qb3+ $1 $146 (13.
Qxd8 {0-1 (36) Prie,E (2499)-Nijboer,F (2566) Belgium 2010}) 13... Kh8 14. Rad1
$16 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gc3d5,Gc3b5] with Nd5 and Nb5 coming up next White stands
clearly better due to the pressure in the centre and on the queenside.}) 12.
Qd2 $146 {[%cal Ga1d1] Seems to be the best preparing to bring the rook to d1
and creating pressure on the d-file.} (12. Rc1 {0-1 (29) Zajic,M (2477)
-Mamedov,R (2645) Batumi GEO 2019}) 12... e4 13. Nd4 Nde5 14. Rad1 $16 {
White is clearly better because of his dominance on the d-file.}) 11. Rc1 e4 {
White closes the centre and prepares to start action on the kingside.} 12. Nd2
g5 $1 {The pawn march continues.} 13. f3 {White decides to do something before
he gets rolled over by Black's pawn avalanche.} exf3 14. Nxf3 {[%cal Gd4d5,
Gf3d4] White intends to play d5 followed by Nd4.} (14. Bxf3 Ne7 15. Qc2 Nf6 16.
Rce1 Ng6 $36 {[%cal Gg6h4] gives Black good attacking chances.}) 14... g4 $1 {
Timing is important. Black does not allow White to play d5.} 15. hxg4 fxg4 16.
Nd2 {[%csl Rg4]} Bh6 $1 {[%csl Re3] counter-attacking the e3 pawn.} 17. Rxf8+
Qxf8 18. Nf1 Nf6 $11 {and Black is doing fine in this position. ½-½ (49)
Ethereal 12.43 (3470)-Stockfish 202008260719_nn-822 (3551) tcec-chess.com INT
2020}) (6... c5 7. h3 {transposes}) (6... Nh5 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nfd2 $1
Nf4 10. exf4 gxh4 11. c3 $11 {is a playable position for both sides but I
prefer White slightly as Black's Kingside structure is weak.}) 7. h3 {[%cal
Gf4h2] Vacating the h2-square for the bishop.} b6 (7... Qe8 {By moving the
queen away from the d-file (avoiding tactics), Black prepares to break with ...
e5.} 8. c4 (8. Bh2 e5 9. Na3 {was a slightly rare move once tried by GM
Naiditsch against GM Gupta.} a6 {is the simplest move for Black covering the
b5 square with a normal position.} (9... exd4 {1-0 (69) Naiditsch,A (2684)
-Gupta,A (2626) Douglas 2016})) 8... e5 9. Bh2 Qe7 10. Nc3 c6 {this is the
favoured line of GM Mamedyarov.} 11. Qc2 Re8 12. b4 (12. dxe5 $2 {White should
avoid exchaning with dxe5 unless it is very necessary.} Nxe5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14.
Rfd1 Bf5 15. Bd3 Bxd3 16. Rxd3 Rad8 17. Rad1 Rxd3 18. Qxd3 h5 19. Bg3 Qe6 20.
Bh4 e4 21. Qe2 Nd7 $15 {0-1 (40) Tabatabaei,M (2629)-Mamedyarov,S (2770) chess.
com INT 2020})) ({It is important to note that} 7... Re8 {does not prepare the
...e5 break. For example after,} 8. Bh2 e5 $2 {would be a huge tactical error
which I have seen Black committ in many blitz games. White simply wins a pawn
after,} (8... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7e5] intending to play ...Bb7 and then ...e5
is the right way to go for Black.}) 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 $1 $16 {1-0 (56)
Bujisho,B (2290)-Shahade,G (2476) chess.com INT 2020}) (7... e5 $2 {does not
work with the knight on d7.} 8. dxe5 Ne4 9. Qd5 $1 dxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Qxe4
$16 {and White ends up a clear pawn up.}) 8. c4 Bb7 {Black has developed his
minor pieces on the queenside and can now prepare the ...e5 break next.} 9. Nc3
(9. Qc2 Ne4 {[%cal Ge7e5] an active way of preparing the ...e5 break.} 10. d5
$6 {This was recently tried by GM Jumabayev. White cuts the support of the
e4-knight but Black has a nice counter-attacking response! [#]} (10. Rd1 {
prevents ...e5 for the time being, but Black immediately prepares it with,} Qe8
11. Nbd2 e5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Bh2 Nxd2 $146 (13... Ndc5 {1/2-1/2 (51) Fauland,
A (2275)-Portisch,F (2420) Vienna 1986}) 14. Nxd2 a5 $15 {[%cal Gd7c5] Black
stands slightly better due to better centre control.}) 10... e5 $1 11. dxe6 (
11. Bh2 f5 $15 {[%csl Ge4,Ye5,Yf5] The knight on e4 is stable and Black has
gained valuable space on the Kingside with ...e5 and ...f5.}) 11... fxe6 12.
Nbd2 Ndc5 13. Rad1 a5 14. Bh2 Qf6 15. Nd4 Nxf2 $1 $146 {would have won the
game for Black.} (15... Nxd2 {1-0 (39) Jumabayev,R (2654)-Godzwon,I (2347)
chess.com INT 2020}) 16. Bg3 Qg5 $19) 9... Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] this is the
most direct way of preparing the ...e5 break.} (9... Re8 10. Bh2 e5 {is
another popular way of breaking with ...e5.}) 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Bh2 (11. Ng5
Bb7 12. Bf3 Qc8 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7] aiming to replace the bishop on b7, Black is
doing fine. 1/2-1/2 (25) Schulze,M (2099)-Hecht,C (2242) Dortmund 2016}) (11.
Qd2 {was played in a recent game.} e5 12. Bh2 Qe7 13. Rfd1 Rad8 {[%csl Gd7]
[%cal Gd8d1]} 14. Rac1 Bb7 15. b4 Rfe8 16. Qc2 {[#]} Bxf3 $1 {Black spots a
nice tactical idea!} 17. Bxf3 exd4 18. exd4 Bxd4 $1 $15 {[%cal Re7e1,Re1g1]
exploiting the back-rannk weakness. 0-1 (27) Kaliksteyn,A (2394)-Yoo,C (2430)
New York USA 2020}) 11... c5 {This alternative break with ...e5 is also fine
for Black.} (11... e5 {is ofcourse the main way of playing in this structure.})
12. Rc1 Qc7 13. b3 (13. Nd2 Bb7 14. Nb1 $1 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3] was an
interesting manoeuver for White with a pleasant position.}) 13... Qb7 14. d5
Bxf3 15. Bxf3 $6 {this allows Black to mount pressure on the queenside.} (15.
gxf3 $14 {was essential, keeping Black's queenside activity in check.}) 15...
b5 16. cxb5 a6 $1 {and Black got a huge counterplay on the queenside. 0-1 (49)
Gelashvili,T (2575)-Can,E (2565) Baku 2016} *

