{[#] On the diagram, you can see the basic structure which arises in the
systems with ...d7-d5. You can expect to face this structure against people
who play Gruenfeld Defence as Black. The global philosophy of White's setup is
based on the fact that Black's dark-squared bishop is restricted by the
central pawn chain. At the same time, White's f4-bishop supports the queenside
play. When looking at the board, the central tension is the first thing that
comes to our mind. All the structures that I am going to cover in this lecture
arise as a result of structural modifications in the centre. In this lecture,
I examine the following modifications of the pawn structure: 1) Black plays ...
c5-c4 2) Black carries out the advance ...e7-e5 3) Reversed Carlsbad structure
arising after ...cxd4 exd4 4) Exchange Slav structure arising after ...cxd4
cxd4. The knowledge of these 4 typical structures will arm you with confidence
when you play these positions with both colours.}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structure with ...c5-c4"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "6k1/pp2pp1p/6p1/3p4/2pP4/2P1P3/PP3PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "0"]
[SourceVersionDate "2021.02.20"]

{This is one of the most important structures for the systems with ...d7-d5.
It arises when Black releases the central tension by means of ...c5-c4. In
general, Black goes for this advance when White has already played Qb3. In
this way, by releasing the central tension, Black wants to eliminate the
indirect pressure that the b3-queen and the d1-rook put on the d5-pawn. If
Black has a queen on b6, the exchange of the queens on b6 usually improves
Black's pawn structure since after ...axb6, the a8-rook enters the game.
Additionally, Black will be ready to win space with ...b6-b5-b4. White's play
usually goes around the ideas b2-b3 and e3-e4. Very often he puts the queen on
a3 and immediately follows with b2-b3. The structure arising after ...cxb3
axb3 favours White unless Black has some concrete counterplay (mainly based on
the c3-pawn). After axb3, White can start gaining space on the queenside.
There are two ways to do so: 1) c3-c4-c5 followed by b3-b4-b5 2) b3-b4-b5
followed by c3-c4 When the queenside is closed, White's main idea is e3-e4-e5
with the idea to go for a kingside attack. Usually, Black does not have time
to execute the advance ...b7-b5-b4. Therefore, he mostly tries to play ...
e7-e5 under favourable circumstances. A typical idea is ...Rfc8 followed by ...
Bf8 and ...e7-e5, underlining the drawbacks of the move Qb3. In the positions
after b2-b3, Black should play very dynamically in order to balance the
inferior pawn structure. With precise play from both sides, the positions are
quite balanced.}  *

