{This structure arises when White has answered Black's ...e7-e5 with dxe5.
With colours reversed, we have the same structure in Scandinavian Defence,
Caro-Kann Defence, and Slav Defence. Black's space advantage in the centre is
compensated by the vulnerability of the d5-pawn. White's strategy is based on
the following elements: 1) Put pressure on the d5-pawn by means of simple
moves such as Qb3, Rd1 (with the idea to double the rooks), and Bf3 after the
prior Ne5 2) Exchange minor pieces in order to reduce the impact of Black's
space advantage. In the endgame, the d5-pawn is even more vulnerable 3) Create
additional weaknesses on the queenside by advancing the a-pawn. This idea
works extremely well when Black had already played ...b7-b6. After a2-a4-a5,
White can either play a5-a6, fixing the a7-pawn or create a weakness on b6 by
means of axb6. Very often the advance of the a-pawn spoils Black's
coordination which allows White to destroy Black's centre. 3) Sometimes, White
plays b2-b4 in order to deflect the c5-pawn, thus weakening the d4-square. The
drawback of this move is that Black's g7-bishop is getting very strong. On the
other hand, Black should try to keep as many pieces as possible. Keeping the
knights is especially important in positions with a space advantage. Black's
main source of counterplay is the advance ...d5-d4. This idea, however,
requires precise calculation. Practice shows that in positions without knights
on the board, Black can even afford to play ...c5-c4, stopping c3-c4 and
preparing the advance ...b7-b5-b4. In this case, Black should only reckon with
the break e3-e4.}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
