[SourceVersionDate "2021.02.20"]

{We have a Carlsbad structure with colours reversed. Such positions arise when
White answers ...cxd4 with exd4. With a bishop on g7, this structure is
considered to be favourable for White. Black's problem is that he does not
have a straightforward counterplay. When the bishop is on g7, the minority
attack on the queenside almost never works. On the other hand, White's firm
control over the e5-square does not allow Black to easily prepare the advance.
..e7-e5. Even if Black manages to execute the break ...e7-e5, after dxe5, he
should be ready to defend a slightly passive position with IQP. A very
important point to remember is that the move ...g7-f6 (preparing ...e7-e5)
should be answered with c3-c4. Once White manages to neutralize Black's
immediate attempts for a counterplay, he can start combining the pressure on
the e-file with a kingside play. Doubling the rooks on the e-file and bringing
the pieces to the kingside followed by pushing the h-pawn is a typical way to
develop the kingside play. My conclusion is that this structure is difficult
for Black.}  *

