{[#] This typical Slav structure can arise via the London move order as well.
This happens when White answers ...cxd4 with cxd4. I believe that such
positions are slightly favourable for White due to the difference in the
activity of the dark-squared bishops. While the f4-bishop supports White's
queenside play, his colleague is bitting on granite. In this structure, both
sides are trying to develop a queenside play. The control of the c-file is the
most important positional factor. Additionally, both sides are trying to win
space on the queenside and take squares c5 and respectively c4 under control.
Having a bishop on g7, Black often fails to take control of the important dark
squares on the queenside. My conclusion is that White's play is easier.}  *

