{[%evp 0,53,26,14,14,13,27,27,34,36,35,33,35,22,14,14,48,42,100,93,102,99,102,
84,105,123,129,128,117,112,138,159,159,71,238,131,155,144,144,144,228,168,204,
204,198,194,203,112,341,346,533,528,620,418,523,426] First of all, we shall
take a look at an example which illustrates the danger of the premature ...
c5-c4. The first important position in the game arose after the moves} 1. d4 d5
2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h3 O-O 6. Be2 c5 7. c3 {We have reached the
most thematic structure for the lines with ...d7-d5. As explained in the
introduction, White aims at provoking his opponent to clarify the situation in
the centre by means of ...c5-c4 or ...cxd4. In the game, Black went for the
immediate} c4 $2 {which is a serious positional mistake. Black usually plays
this move when winning a tempo. For example, the advance ...c5-c4 works well
when the white queen is already committed to b3. White immediately took
advantage of Black's mistake and played} 8. b3 $1 {It turns out that Black's
development is not enough to sustain the space.} b5 $2 {Another serious
mistake. Black insists on his initially wrong strategy. Now, his queenside
will be destroyed.} ({Better would have been} 8... cxb3 9. axb3 Nc6 $16 {
accepting an inferior pawn structure. White's typical plan is to go for a
queenside expansion. Besides the immediate c3-c4 followed by Nc3, White often
start with b3-b4-b5, thus fixing the a7-pawn. Only after that, he can carry
out the break c3-c4.}) 9. a4 $1 {This is the way to use the unprotected
a8-rook. Black cannot play ...a7-a6.} cxb3 10. axb5 $18 {[%csl Rb3] The
b3-pawn will be lost. Besides his healthy extra pawn, White would enjoy a
superior piece activity as well. The rest is a matter of simple technique.} b2
11. Ra2 a6 12. O-O Qb6 13. Rxb2 Bd7 14. Na3 Rc8 15. Qb3 axb5 16. Nxb5 Ra5 17.
Rfb1 Nc6 18. c4 dxc4 19. Bxc4 Be8 20. Ng5 Nd8 21. Nc7 Qxb3 22. Rxb3 Rxg5 23.
Rb8 Rxb8 24. Rxb8 Ra5 25. Rxd8 Kf8 26. Be5 Ra7 27. Nxe8 1-0

