{Now, we shall take a look at an example in which Black's ...c5-c4 was more
justified. In this game, the famous London expert GM Boris Grachev provides a
clear illustration of White's plan. Despite the inaccuracies, the game remains
very instructive.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 d5 6. h3 c5
7. c3 Qb6 {This is much more logical than the immediate ...c5-c4 which was
seen in the previous game. Black will go for this advance only after provoking
Qb3.} 8. Qb3 Nc6 9. Nbd2 c4 {Now, Black is more or less forced to go for this
move.} ({The problem is that a simple developing move such as} 9... Bf5 {
would run into} 10. dxc5 Qxc5 11. Qxb7 $16 {when White enjoys a healthy extra
pawn.}) 10. Qa3 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ga3e7,Gb2b3] I believe a3 is the best square
for the queen in this structure. From this position, the queen supports b2-b3
and puts pressure along the diagonal a3-f8. Of course, White should always pay
attention to Black's ideas based on ...Bf8.} ({A bit passive is} 10. Qc2 Bf5
11. Qc1 Rfc8 12. O-O Qd8 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] Black is planning to start his
queenside expansion by playing ...b7-b5-b4. In our first London camp, we have
examined the same structure (with Black's dark-squared bishop being on the
diagonal f8-a3). Being on g5, the bishop is restricted by White's central pawn
chain. On the other hand, however, the fianchetto provides some advantages as
well. For example, in some cases, Black can prepare the central break ...e7-e5
by means of Nd7.}) ({Usually, the endgame arising after} 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. O-O
b5 12. a3 Bf5 {[%csl Ga4,Rb2][%cal Gh7h6,Gg6g5,Gf6d7,Gd7b6,Gb6a4] is
favourable for Black. As explained in the first London camp, Black will try to
bring his knight to a6 by using the route f6-d7-b6-a4. Of course, before doing
so, it is advisable to secure the position of the slightly exposed
light-squared bishop by playing ...h7-h6 followed by ...g6-g5.}) 10... Qd8 {
This move is slightly passive. To my understanding, before retreating with the
queen, Black should try to bring his king's rook to c8, thus making the
f8-square available for the bishop.} ({As we are going to witness in the next
games, more to the point would have been} 10... Bf5 11. O-O Rfc8 {[%cal Gg7f8,
Gb6d8]}) 11. b3 b5 12. O-O {[%cal Ga3b2,Ga2a4] As we have seen in the previous
game, after provoking ... b7-b5, White should try to attack Black's queenside
structure by means a2-a4. Therefore, White can consider playing Qb2 on the
next move.} Nd7 $6 {This move is a mistake. Black loses control of the
e4-square which makes the break e3-e4 possible.} ({More logical would have been
} 12... Bf5 {developing the bishop and taking the e4-square under control.
Although not forced, the following line illustrates the character of the game
in such structures.} 13. Qb2 Qd7 14. a4 a6 15. Rfd1 {[%csl Rd5,Rd7][%cal Gd1d7,
Gf3e5,Gd4e5,Gd1d5] As we are going to see on many occasions, putting indirect
pressure on d5 is an important idea in such structures. White will play Ne5
and recapture with a pawn in case of an exchange.} Rfc8 16. axb5 axb5 17. bxc4
bxc4 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. Ne5 {[%cal Gd1d7] We can now see the point behind 15.
Rfd1.} Qc8 20. Bf3 {[%cal Gd2c4] After Ne5, the bishop usually occupies the
f3-square. Now, the threat is Ndxc4. The game might continue} Nxe5 21. dxe5 Ne4
22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Qb5 $14 {Even though the position is objectively equal,
White is pressing a bit.}) 13. bxc4 bxc4 14. e4 {After this typical break,
White enjoys an obvious advantage.} e6 15. Qd6 {Grachev wants to force the
transition into a favourable endgame.} ({Keeping the queens with} 15. Rfe1 {
would have been even more precise. Black is completely tied while White has
obvious ways to improve the position. A possible idea is to play Rab1 followed
by the manoeuvre Bd1-a4.}) 15... Ndb8 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Rfb1 {[%cal Ge2d1,
Gd1a4] One can ask why Grachev prefers to occupy the b-file with his f1-rook.
What exactly does the a1-rook in this position. Actually, keeping a rook on a1
is an important positional idea in such structures. The a1-rook often supports
the advance of the a-pawn. White is now planning the typical manoeuvre Bd1-a4.
Concerning the central tension, he can play exd5 followed by Nf1-e3, thus
putting an annoying pressure on d5.} Ba6 18. Bd1 $6 {This move gives Black
extra options. White should now reckon with the advance ...e6-e5.} ({I would
have preferred} 18. exd5 exd5 19. Nf1 Nd7 20. Ne3 Nf6 21. Nd2 {[%cal Ge2f3]
with Bf3 to follow. Black is under terrible pressure.}) 18... Nd7 $2 {This
passive move allows White to stabilize his advantage.} ({The dynamic} 18... e5
$1 {would have provided Black with decent counter chances.} 19. exd5 exf4 20.
dxc6 Nxc6 21. Ba4 Rac8 22. Bxc6 Rxc6 23. Rb4 $14 {Even though White keeps a
slight edge, Black has good chances to equalize.}) 19. exd5 exd5 20. Ba4 Rac8
21. Bb5 {By exchanging the passive a6-bishop, Grachev wants to invade via the
b-file.} ({Maybe even more convincing would have been} 21. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1e3]}
Nb6 22. Bxc6 Rxc6 23. a4 $1 {We can now see the point behind keeping the rook
on a1. White is planning to increase the pressure on d5 by playing Ne3
followed by a4-a5.} Nd7 24. Ne3 Nf6 25. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Ga1a2,Ga2b2] White is
ready to double the rook on the b-file. Black has no counterplay.}) 21... Bxb5
22. Rxb5 Nf8 23. g4 $2 {Overlooking Black's counterplay.} ({After the cautious
} 23. Bg3 {White would have kept his edge.}) 23... Ne6 24. Bg3 $2 {Allowing
the sacrifice on d4.} ({Better was} 24. Be3 {, accepting the mistake.}) 24...
Rd7 $2 {Black misses a golden opportunity.} ({After} 24... Bxd4 25. cxd4 Ncxd4
26. Nxd4 Nxd4 27. Ra5 Ne2+ 28. Kg2 c3 $11 {Black has at least equal chances.})
25. Re1 h6 26. Nf1 $2 {Once again, White allows the sacrifice on d4.} ({
The simple} 26. Kg2 {would have provided a stable advantage. Now, the
sacrifices on d4 do not work -} Bxd4 27. Nxd4 Ncxd4 28. cxd4 Nxd4 29. Rb8 Rxb8
30. Bxb8 {and White is winning.}) 26... Kh7 $2 {Mistakes continue.} ({The
simple} 26... Bxd4 $1 {would have given Black more than enough counterplay.}
27. Rxe6 {Only move} ({After} 27. cxd4 Nexd4 $19 {Black is winning.}) 27...
fxe6 28. Nxd4 Nxd4 29. cxd4 c3 30. Ne3 c2 31. Nxc2 Rxc2 32. Rb8+ Kf7 33. Be5
$11 {White's compensation is enough for a draw.}) 27. Kg2 $16 {After this move,
White finally managed to consolidate his advantage. Later on, after some
mutual inaccuracies, he managed to convert the advantage.} Bf6 28. Ne3 Rcd8 29.
Nc2 Re8 30. a3 Be7 31. Nb4 Bxb4 32. axb4 f6 33. Ra1 Kg7 34. h4 Kf7 35. Ra6 Rc8
36. g5 hxg5 37. hxg5 Nxg5 38. Nxg5+ fxg5 39. Rc5 Ne7 40. Be5 Rf8 41. Rca5 Ra8
42. Ra1 Rb7 43. Rh1 Rb6 44. Rha1 Nc8 45. R6a5 Ke6 46. Re1 Nd6 47. Bxd6+ Kxd6
48. Re5 Rf8 49. Rxg5 Kc7 50. Rgxd5 Rbf6 51. Ra2 Kb6 52. Rc5 1-0

