{The next example shows that even an experienced grandmaster might become a
victim of White's annoying positional pressure. After failing to obtain
counterplay in his game against Maxim Dlugy, Alexei Dreev didn't withstand the
pressure and lost quickly.} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h3 O-O
6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 Qb6 8. Qb3 c4 {This move usually transposes to the more
common 8...Nc6 9.Be2 c4.} 9. Qa3 Nc6 10. b3 {Playing b2-b3 before Be2 might
lead to a double-edged play.} cxb3 11. axb3 Bf5 {This move actually transposes
to the lines with 8...Nc6 9.Be2 c4 10.Qa3 Bf5.} ({I think that Black should
have tried to make use of the better development by playing} 11... Ne4 {
This jump is typically well met by} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nd2 {when White usually
enjoys a pleasant advantage due to the better pawn structure. Nevertheless,
Black's better development provides him with excellent dynamic opportunities.
For example, he can proceed with} e5 $1 14. Bg3 Be6 $132 {White should now
reckon with the advance ...f5-f4. The play is getting extremely double-edged.})
12. Be2 a5 {Preventing the advance b3-b4 and securing good control of the
b4-square in case of c3-c4. On the other hand, with his last move, Black
weakens the b5-square. Maxim Dlugy takes advantage of this drawback.} 13. O-O
Rfc8 14. Rfc1 Bf8 {[%cal Ge7e5] As we already know, ...Rfc8 followed by ...Bf8
is a typical operation in such structures. In this position, however, White has
} 15. Qa4 {when the queen is very well placed on a4. The point is that} Bd7 {
can be answered with} 16. Bb5 {making use of the weakened light squares. White
is now planning to proceed with c3-c4. After an exchange on c4 (...dxc4 bxc4),
White's pressure along the b-file will be very annoying. Failing to find a
concrete counterplay, Dreev decided to complicate the game at any price by
playing} e5 $2 {which just loses a pawn.} ({More tenacious would have been} 
16... Be8 17. c4 Nb4 18. Bxe8 Nxe8 {with good chances to neutralize White's
slight pressure.}) 17. Bg5 Bg7 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. dxe5 $16 {White enjoys a
healthy extra pawn. Later on, after some mutual inaccuracies, he managed to
win.} Bg7 20. e4 (20. c4 $1 $16) 20... Be6 21. exd5 Bxd5 22. Re1 Qc5 23. Bc4
Bxc4 24. Nxc4 b5 25. Qa3 Qxa3 26. Nxa3 b4 27. cxb4 Nxb4 28. Nc4 Rxc4 29. bxc4
Nc2 30. c5 a4 31. c6 a3 32. c7 Bf8 33. Red1 Rc8 34. Rac1 Rxc7 35. Ne1 Ra7 1-0

