{In the next game, we are going to demonstrate Black's best way to handle the
structures arising after ...c5-c4. The first important moment arises after} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 d5 6. h3 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. O-O Qb6
9. Qb3 c4 10. Qa3 Bf5 11. Nbd2 {We have seen this position on a number of
occasions. Now, Black played what I consider to be the most precise reaction -}
Rfc8 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Rc3][%cal Gc8c3,Gg7f8,Ge7e5] There two main ideas behind
this strong positional move: 1) Since the f8-square is now available for the
bishop, White should reckon with the idea ...Bf8 followed by ...e7-e5 2) By
putting the rook on c8, Black anticipates the advance ...b2-b3. In some cases,
the c3-pawn might be under pressure.} 12. b3 {White cannot spend further time
on preparing this move since ...Bf8 followed by ...e7-e5 is on the agenda.} Bf8
{I am not sure about this move. White wants to play Qb2 anyway.} ({The
critical answer would have been} 12... Bd3 $1 13. Bxd3 {White's only chance is
to create a weak pawn on d3 and put pressure. Nevertheless, it turns out that
Black's dynamic resources compensate for this weakness.} ({After} 13. Rfe1 Bxe2
14. Rxe2 cxb3 15. axb3 a5 {[%cal Gb6a6,Gb7b5] Black is doing perfectly fine.
He is ready to proceed with ...Qa6 followed by ...b7-b5.}) 13... cxd3 {In this
position, there are 3 dynamic ideas for Black: 1) ...Ne4 2) The advance ...
a7-a5-a4 3) The central break ...e7-e5 It seems that White will have a hard
time trying to stop all of them. In my opinion, the most critical continuation
is} 14. Qb2 {Besides preparing Qb1 at some point, White is also planning to
meet ...a7-a5 with a2-a4.} ({In case of} 14. Rac1 {the counterplay based on} a5
15. Qb2 a4 {seems to be sufficient.} 16. Qb1 ({Playing} 16. b4 {is a
concession. The weakness of c3 and c4 would always provide Black with enough
counterplay. One of the possible ideas is} Ne4 17. Qb1 Nxd2 18. Nxd2 Qb5 $132 {
[%cal Ge7e5] planning ...e7-e5.}) 16... Qa6 17. Rfd1 axb3 18. axb3 Ne4 $132 {
Once again, it transpires that White cannot easily win the d3-pawn. He should
always take care of the c3-pawn and watch for the ...e7-e5 break.}) 14... a5
15. a4 Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 16. Rac1 e5 17. dxe5 Ncxe5 {This is the most natural
continuation.} ({The alternative} 17... Bxe5 $5 {also deserves attention.
Having more space, Black tries to keep both his knights on the board.} 18. Nxe5
Ncxe5 19. Qb1 Rc6 {The position remains unclear. Black, however, should play
energetically in order to balance the absence of the dark-squared bishop.}) 18.
Bxe5 {White is going for the following sequence:} Nxe5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Nf3
Bf6 21. Rfd1 Qa6 22. Qb1 b5 23. Qxd3 bxa4 24. bxa4 Qxd3 25. Rxd3 Rc4 26. Rxd5
Rxa4 $14 {Black has enough compensation for the pawn. Nevertheless, he should
still be careful.}) 13. Qb2 cxb3 $6 {With a bishop on f8, Black will not
manage to create counterplay in this structure.} ({Computer insists that even} 
13... Bg7 {shoud have been preferred.}) 14. axb3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gb4b5,Gc3c4,
Ga1a2,Gf1a1] White can think of employing his classical plan - b3-b4-b5
followed by c3-c4. Since the a7-pawn is fixed, doubling the rooks on the
a-file also makes a lot of sense.} a5 15. Ra2 h6 16. Rfa1 g5 17. Bh2 Ra7 $6 {
This move is pointless. Even though Black's position is by no means lost, the
lack of concrete counterplay makes it difficult to keep finding useful moves.}
18. Ne5 e6 19. Ra4 Nxe5 20. Bxe5 Nd7 21. Bg3 {Now, Black should reckon with
the advance b3-b4. The position is very difficult from a practical point of
view.} Bb4 $4 {This blunder loses the game.} 22. cxb4 $1 $18 Rc2 23. bxa5 Rxb2
24. axb6 Rxa4 25. Rxa4 Rxd2 26. Ra8+ Kg7 27. Bb5 Nxb6 28. Rb8 Bd3 29. Be5+ Kg6
30. Rg8+ Kf5 31. Bxd3+ Rxd3 32. f3 1-0

