{In the next model game, we are going to take a look at another important
strategy - White closes the queenside and starts playing in the centre and on
the kingside. In this position, the famous London expert GM Nikola Sedlak
started with} 9. a4 {which is a typical move in this pawn structure. White is
planning to proceed with a4-a5. Then, depending on the concrete circumstances,
he can either create a weakness on b6 with axb6 or opt for a5-a6, thus
creating a potentially dangerous reserve passed pawn. In order to prevent
a4-a5 Black played} Nc6 10. Ne5 {Exchanging the c6-knight with Ne5 is a
thematic idea. Without the c6-knight, White can consider playing a4-a5 or
b2-b4. The game followed with} e6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. b4 $1 {Remember this
thematic idea. White wants to provoke the advance ...c5-c4. When the central
tension is released and the queenside closed, White can focus on his play in
the centre by preparing the advance e3-e4.} c4 13. b5 Bb7 14. Bf3 {[%csl Gf3]
[%cal Gd2c4] The f3-square is a good spot for the bishop. Besides supporting
the advance e3-e4, the bishop creates an annoying pressure on the long
diagonal. Now, the concrete threat is Nxc4 on the next move.} Qd7 15. Qb1 $1 {
[%cal Gb1b4,Ga4a5] In order to completely close the queenside, White needs to
provoke the advance ...a7-a5. Therefore, he is planning to proceed with Qb4
followed by a4-a5, thus creating a dangerous queenside pressure.} a6 16. Qb4
Rfd8 17. Rfb1 {Now, White is ready to open the queenside. His next move will
be 18.bxa6 followed by a4-a5. Therefore, Black decided to close the queenside
by playing} a5 {This is exactly what White was hoping for.} ({Maybe, more to
the point would have been} 17... Ra7 {After} 18. bxa6 Rxa6 19. a5 Rda8 20. Qb2
{Black can get rid of the pressure in an elegant way:} b5 $1 21. Qxb5 Bc6 22.
Qb2 Rxa5 23. Rxa5 Rxa5 {The position is almost equal.}) 18. Qb2 Ne8 $6 {
Black shouldn't have allowed the advance e3-e4 so easily.} ({Better would have
been} 18... Qc8 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge6e5] trying to prepare ...e6-e5 with ...Nd7.})
19. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3g4] White is planning to play
e4-e5. Afterwards, he can gradually bring his pieces to the kingside and
prepare the advance of the h-pawn. A typical idea would be the manoeuvre
Nd2-f1-e3-g4 followed by Qd2 and Bh6.} f5 $2 {This move is already a huge
positional mistake. Black weakens the kingside and the e5-square.} ({The
position was calling for dynamic measures. Therefore, regardless of the
objective evaluation, Black should have played} 19... e5 {Nevertheless, after}
20. Bxe5 Bxe5 21. dxe5 d4 22. Nxc4 Qc7 23. cxd4 Qxc4 24. d5 {White has a
fantastic position.}) 20. exf5 {Since Black has weakened the e5-square, White
changes his initial strategy - he decides to start playing on the e-file.} ({
Of course, playing} 20. e5 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Gg2g3,Gg1g2,Gb1h1]
would have been a decent option as well. White has an easy game. He can
proceed with h2-h4, Nd2-f1-e3 followed by g2-g3, Kg2 and Rh1. The kingside
attack is overwhelming.}) 20... exf5 21. Re1 Nf6 22. Be5 Ne4 {At this point,
White should go for the right exchange strategy. Due to the weakness of
Black's dark squares, White's dream position would be Q&N against Q&B (the
light-squared one). That's what Sedlak managed to achieve.} 23. Bxg7 ({Maybe a
bit more precise move order would have been} 23. Bxe4 fxe4 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. f3
{Transposing to the game but ruling out the option of 23...Nxd2.}) 23... Kxg7 (
{After} 23... Nxd2 24. Qxd2 Kxg7 25. Re5 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gd2e3,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White
has a winning advantage. He can proceed with Rae1 and Qe3 followed by h2-h4-h5.
}) 24. Bxe4 fxe4 25. f3 Qe6 26. Qc2 Rf8 27. Re3 Rae8 28. Rae1 Qf6 29. Qd1 Qf7
30. Qe2 exf3 31. Nxf3 $18 {White got the position he was dreaming of. Due to
the weak dark squares, White's kingside attack cannot be stopped. The game is
over.} Rxe3 32. Qxe3 Bc8 33. Ng5 Qf4 34. Qe7+ Kh6 35. Nf3 Rf7 36. Qd8 Bg4 37.
Qh4+ Kg7 38. Ng5 1-0

