{So far we have been dealing with the structures arising after the advance ...
c5-c4. In practice, Black often goes for another popular plan - preparing the
advance ...e7-e5. As explained in the introduction to this structure, we will
get a type of position which is typical for Caro-Kann, Scandinavian, Slav, etc.
We start the coverage of this structure with the game Dominguez - Mamedyarov.
Even though this is a blitz game, I think that the quality of play was pretty
high. After the normal moves} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 g6 4. e3 Bg7 5. h3 O-O
6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Be2 {instead of 8...Qb6, Mamedyarov went for} Nd7 {
[%cal Ge7e5] indicating his intention to proceed with ...e7-e5. The first
important crossroads arises after} 9. O-O e5 10. dxe5 Ndxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12.
Nf3 {So far, all the moves have been logical. Having less space, White is
trying to exchange minor pieces. White's idea is that in the endgame, the
d5-pawn might be vulnerable.} Nc6 {Conceptually speaking, this move should be
preferred. Black wants to keep as many pieces on the board as possible. On the
other hand, however, now White has time to organize his pressure on d5.} ({
The alternative direction is} 12... Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Be6 {White can now put his
typical pressure on d5 -} 14. Qb3 {White is ready to double his rooks along
the d-file.} Qd7 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Rd2 Qc6 17. Rfd1 $14 {Even though Black
should be able to hold this position, White's pressure is a bit annoying.
Black should always reckon with c3-c4 or Qa3 followed by b2-b4.}) 13. Qb3 {
[%cal Gf1d1] The idea is Rfd1. The pressure on b7 prevents Black from
developing his light-squared bishop to e6. Therefore, Mamedyarov is forced to
accept a slightly inferior structure. He played} c4 14. Qa3 Be6 15. Rfd1 Qb6 {
This is the critical position for the evaluation of the entire concept related
to 12...Nc6. As compensation for the weakness of d5-pawn and d4-square, Black
has a space advantage on the queenside. If Black manages to neutralize the
pressure on d5 and prepare the advance ...b7-b5-b4, he will be better. White,
however, has important resources at his disposal.} 16. Bd6 {White is planning
to proceed with Bc5 followed by Nd4. This plan, however, is a bit slow. In the
meantime, Black will prepare his counterplay.} ({The game Kamsky - Dourerassou,
2020 continued} 16. Rd2 Rfd8 17. Rad1 {1-0 (51) Kamsky,G (2674) -Dourerassou,
J (2477) chess.com INT 2020 At this point, Black could have played} h6 {
when it's not so clear how can White increase the pressure.}) ({I believe that
White should try to take the bishop pair by means of} 16. Ng5 {when the game
might continue} Rad8 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Rab1 $16 {[%csl Ge2,Gf4][%cal Gb2b3]
White enjoys a stable advantage due to the bishop pair. This advantage is
increased by the asymmetrical pawn structure - there are many breaks allowing
White to open the position up. He is ready to follow with b2-b3.}) 16... Rfd8
17. Bc5 Qc7 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Bf8 20. Qa4 b5 {Since there is no longer
pressure on d5, Black can start his queenside play.} 21. Qc2 a5 $11 {The
position is balanced. Later on, neither of the opponents managed to unbalance
the game.} 22. a3 b4 (22... Bf5 23. Qd2 Re8 $11) 23. axb4 axb4 24. cxb4 Bxb4
25. Rxa8 Rxa8 26. Bf3 Bc5 27. Bc3 Rd8 28. Qc1 Qb6 29. Qd2 Rd7 30. h4 h5 31. g3
Kh7 32. Kg2 Bf8 33. Ra1 Bg7 34. Bxg7 Kxg7 35. Qc3+ d4 36. exd4 Qxd4 37. Qxd4+
Rxd4 38. Rd1 Rxd1 39. Bxd1 Kf6 40. f4 Ke7 41. Kf2 Kd6 42. Ke3 Kc5 43. Bc2 Bf5
44. Bd1 Bb1 45. Ba4 Bf5 46. Bd1 Bd7 47. Bc2 Be6 48. Bd1 Bf5 49. Ba4 Be6 50. Bd1
Bf5 51. Ba4 1/2-1/2

