{[%evp 0,59,27,27,27,16,27,29,35,41,14,22,19,19,46,42,32,26,17,14,38,12,24,16,
3,-5,-8,-10,0,-12,84,81,86,80,127,103,109,102,140,104,98,106,104,104,130,139,
142,167,167,181,183,205,198,182,198,198,340,345,969,969,988,1009] In the next
example, we are going to see the tactical vulnerability of Black's centre.
Additionally, this game illustrates the power of the advance a2-a4-a5.} 1. d4
d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 g6 4. e3 Bg7 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. h3 b6 7. c3 Bb7 8. Be2 Nbd7 {
On d7, the knight does not stand in the way of the bishop. Additionally, Black
can comfortably execute the advance ...c7-c5. Nevertheless, there is one major
drawback of Black's setup. With a Black knight on d7, White can easily execute
the advantage a2-a4-a5.} 9. O-O Ne4 10. a4 $1 {This is the point. If allowed,
White is going to push the pawn all the way to a6. If Black plays ... a7-a5
himself, his queenside structure will lose flexibility. Afterwards, playing ...
c7-c5 will dramatically weaken the b5-square.} c5 11. a5 Nxd2 {By deflecting
the f3-knight, Black is planning to play ...e7-e5.} ({Taking on a5 is almost
never good. For example, after} 11... bxa5 12. Nb3 $16 {White would regain the
pawn, thus keeping a better pawn structure.}) 12. Nxd2 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nf3
{As always, White is trying to exchange as many pieces as possible.} Re8 $2 {
Strangely enough, this move loses by force. White can take advantage of
Black's vulnerable centre.} ({The most reliable choice would have been} 14...
Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Qd7 {[%cal Gd5d4] when Black is ready to free himself by means
of ...d5-d4. Nevertheless, after} 16. Qb3 d4 $1 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. cxd4 cxd4 19.
a6 $1 {An important move that shows the benefit of playing a2-a4-a5. As we
know, in every endgame, the a6-pawn is potentially dangerous.} Qe7 20. Rac1 $14
{The superior piece activity as well as the a6-pawn, provide White with a
slight advantage.}) ({Worse is} 14... Nc4 {when after} 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. Qxd8
Rfxd8 17. Bc7 Rdc8 18. axb6 axb6 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Bxb6 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Bf8 22.
Rd1 $16 {Black does not have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 15. Bxe5 ({
Another winning line is} 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Bb5 Re7 17. a6 $1 {Once again,
White makes use of the a-pawn!} Bc8 18. Bc6 Rb8 19. Bxd5 $18 {White is winning.
}) 15... Bxe5 16. Bb5 Re6 17. a6 Bc8 18. e4 $1 {After this strong move,
Black's position collapses. The point is that} d4 {is well met by} 19. Bc4 {
[%cal Gc4d5] planning Bd5. White is winning.} Bg7 (19... Re7 20. Bd5 $18) 20.
Bxe6 Bxe6 21. cxd4 cxd4 22. Qd3 Qc8 23. Rfc1 Qd7 24. e5 Rd8 25. Rd1 Qc7 26.
Rac1 Qb8 27. Qe2 b5 28. Nxd4 Bc8 29. Nc6 Rxd1+ 30. Qxd1 1-0

