{Now, we shall take a look at an example concerning the right exchange
strategy. In this position, Black should decide whether to recapture on e5
with a knight or with a bishop. At this point, Black has played} 16... Nxe5 {
Which is inferior. As we have already pointed out, in positions with a space
advantage, one should keep the knights on the board.} ({Therefore, Black
should have preferred} 16... Bxe5 $1 {A possible follow-up would be} 17. Nxe5
Nxe5 18. b4 Re6 {It turns out that White cannot put additional pressure on the
centre. After} 19. a5 {[%cal Gd2b3]} (19. Nb3 Nc4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ge6c6,Gc4d6,
Gd6e4]}) 19... c4 20. axb6 axb6 21. Ra1 Kg7 22. Ra7 Qf6 {[%cal Ge5d3] Black's
activity and space advantage provide good compensation for White's slightly
better pawn structure.}) 17. Nxe5 Rxe5 18. Nf3 Re6 19. Rd2 {White managed to
achieve the kind of position he wants - queen and knight versus queen and
bishop. After the simplifications, Black's d5-pawn is slightly vulnerable.
Even though Black is objectively fine, this position is practically unpleasant.
} Rc7 20. a5 Rd6 21. Rbd1 Rcd7 22. axb6 axb6 23. Kf1 $1 {A useful prophylactic
move. Besides bringing the king closer to the centre, White steps away from
tactics based on ...Bxf2 check which might happen in the positions after ...
d5-d4.} d4 24. cxd4 cxd4 25. Qb4 d3 $2 {This move is a huge mistake. Now,
Black will not be able to protect the passed pawn.} ({Black should have found} 
25... Bf8 {when after} 26. exd4 Rxd4 27. Qxd4 Rxd4 28. Rxd4 Qf6 29. R1d2 $11 {
the position is balanced.}) 26. Qb3 Qf6 27. Ne1 Bh6 28. Kg1 Qh4 29. Rxd3 Rxd3
30. Rxd3 $18 {White enjoys a healthy extra pawn. His advantage is decisive.}
Rc7 31. Qxb6 Rc1 32. Qd8+ Qxd8 33. Rxd8+ Bf8 34. Kf1 Kg7 35. Ke2 Bb4 36. Nd3
Rc2+ 37. Kd1 Rd2+ 38. Kc1 Ba5 39. Rd5 Kf6 40. e4 h5 41. h4 1-0

