{[%evp 0,63,27,18,18,18,41,41,41,41,34,25,29,30,26,20,20,14,37,-2,-2,0,1,0,0,
15,29,30,30,49,42,38,64,54,72,38,63,66,44,48,26,37,102,56,56,53,52,52,124,102,
100,120,128,127,132,132,152,55,53,53,59,54,56,56,56,-43] The advance ...d5-d4
is always very tricky. Before going for it, Black should make precise
calculations. Very often it turns out that the counter play initiated with the
move ...d5-d4 is premature. We shall now take a look at a typical example. The
first 16 moves are familiar to us.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5.
Be2 d5 6. h3 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Nbd2 Nd7 9. O-O e5 10. dxe5 Ndxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5
12. Nf3 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Be6 14. Qb3 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gd1d2,Gf1d1] White is
preparing his typical pressure on the d-file. He is going to proceed with
doubling the rooks on the d-file.} Qd7 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Rd2 {This is the
first critical position. It's clear that White's next move will be Rfd1. Black
faces a dilemma which is typical for such positions - stay passively or go for
...d5-d4. It's not so easy to decide. In a practical game, you are not sure
that the passive defence would hold. On the other hand, the advance ...d5-d4
is burning all the bridges. Therefore, precise calculation and correct
evaluation are required here. Black played} d4 $6 {which is not the optimal
decision. Intuitively speaking, I would say that Black's activity is not
enough to sustain this central break.} ({The most precise would have been} 
16... Qc6 17. Rfd1 c4 $1 {Gaining space on the queenside and ruling out all
the ideas based on c3-c4.} 18. Qb4 Rd7 {reaching the structure from the game
Dominguez - Mamedyarov. We already know that Black can hold this structure
when there are only bishops on the board. He should only reckon with the
advance e3-e4.}) ({The immediate} 16... c4 {runs into} 17. Qd1 $16 {[%cal
Ge3e4,Gf4g5] Black cannot simultaneously deal with White's threats - e3-e4 and
Bg5.}) 17. Qa3 {It becomes clear that Black's centre is rather shaky.} Qb5 18.
exd4 ({The immediate} 18. Rfd1 $16 {is possible as well.}) 18... cxd4 19. Rfd1
Qb6 $2 {Mistake in a difficult position.} ({More tenacious would have been} 
19... Bd5 20. cxd4 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 Rd5 $16 {putting some resistance.}) 20. Bg5 f6
21. Bf4 ({Even simpler would have been} 21. Rxd4 {with the idea to meet} fxg5 {
with} 22. Rd6 $18) 21... dxc3 22. bxc3 (22. Qxc3 $18) 22... Rxd2 23. Rxd2 {
Despite the equal material, White's piece activity decides the game.} Qa6 24.
Qe7 Qc4 25. Rd8 Qxf4 26. Qxe6+ Kh8 27. Qe7 Qh6 28. Bxb7 $2 (28. Rd7 f5 29. g3
Bxc3 30. Rxb7 $18) 28... Qc1+ 29. Kh2 Qf4+ 30. g3 Qxf2+ 31. Bg2 Rg8 32. Rd7 {
The position is already equal. For some reason, the notation ends here with
the result 1-0.} 1-0

