{[%evp 0,87,26,20,27,27,28,29,34,34,36,32,28,17,17,28,13,16,27,21,72,38,53,63,
67,61,66,69,63,73,70,78,66,66,59,68,72,73,99,63,83,89,80,92,96,80,71,71,66,85,
73,77,77,77,169,188,269,191,181,137,151,157,205,113,191,159,181,224,215,215,
332,334,348,314,360,381,395,393,456,527,640,686,840,1010,1069,693,762,944,1511,
2046] So far we have been dealing with Black's two main ways to clarify the
situation in the centre - ...c5-c4 and ...e7-e5. In the next few games, we
shall examine the reversed Carlsbad structure arising after ...cxd4 exd4. As
pointed out in the introduction to this structure, White usually enjoys a
slight edge since the g-bishop is restricted by White's central pawn chain.
The first model game is Grachev, B - Kyc, J, 2015. After the moves} 1. d4 Nf6
2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 cxd4 8. exd4 {we get
the reversed Carlsbad structure. As we are going to see, it's not easy for
Black to find a constructive plan in such positions. With a bishop on g7, the
minority attack never works. On the other hand, preparing ...e7-e5 is far from
easy since White has good control over the e5-square. This game features a
typical mistake which occurs quite often in such structures -} Qb6 $6 {With
the c5-pawn being exchanged, the queen has nothing to do on b6. As we have
already seen, the main idea of ...Qb6 is to provoke Qb3 which will be answered
with ...c5-c4.} 9. Qb3 Nbd7 $6 {This move blocks the c8-bishop. Black should
have probably started with ...Bf5. Now, it's not clear how Black will complete
the development without accepting major positional concessions.} 10. Be2 Qxb3 {
Generally speaking, this exchange is undesirable for Black. On the other hand,
I don't see another way to complete the development.} 11. axb3 $1 {Of course!
This recapture actually improves White's pawn structure. Now, the a1-rook get
into play. Additionally, White can start gaining space on the queenside
without creating weaknesses. One of the main plans is b3-b4-b5 followed by
doubling the rooks on the a-file.} b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Ba6 $1 {Another strong
move. White fixes the a7-pawn and weakens the c6-square.} Bxa6 14. Rxa6 Nb8 15.
Bxb8 $1 {Maybe Black has underestimated this exchange. When fighting for a
weak square, we try to eliminate the opponent's pieces that control this
square.} Rfxb8 16. Rfa1 Rb7 17. Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c6] The knight is heading for
the weak c6-square.} Ne4 18. Ndf3 Nd6 19. Nc6 Nc8 20. b4 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gb2b3,
Gc3c4] Finally, Grachev starts gaining space on the queenside. The idea is to
fix the a7-pawn and improve the control of the c6-square by playing b4-b5.
Afterwards, White can proceed with b2-b3 followed by c3-c4.} e6 21. b5 Bf8 22.
b3 Rc7 23. c4 dxc4 24. bxc4 $18 {White is strategically winning. Black is in a
kind of a positional zugzwang.} Nd6 25. R1a4 f6 26. Nd2 Nc8 27. Ne4 Kf7 28. Kf1
h6 29. Ke2 f5 30. Nd2 Bg7 31. Nf3 Bf6 32. Kd3 g5 33. c5 bxc5 34. dxc5 Be7 35.
Nfe5+ Kf6 36. Kc4 Rb7 37. Nd4 Nb6+ 38. cxb6 Kxe5 39. Nc6+ Kd6 40. Rxa7 Rbxa7
41. Rxa7 Re8 42. Rxe7 Rxe7 43. Nxe7 Kxe7 44. b7 1-0

