{[%evp 0,83,28,24,27,27,36,33,36,39,102,26,66,16,16,11,20,7,30,33,37,37,41,40,
40,48,44,35,47,54,49,42,44,37,32,40,34,52,45,42,58,40,38,45,43,43,52,47,65,69,
71,39,45,43,168,163,229,232,235,237,300,302,353,361,377,395,383,398,419,419,
421,393,382,413,435,357,472,504,562,543,584,571,753,802,802,905] Let's take a
look at one more example dedicated to the exchange of the queens on b3.
Contrary to the previous example, in this game, Black demonstrated more
stubborn defence.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 d5 6. h3 O-O
7. Be2 Nc6 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 Qb6 {Once again, I remind you that this move is
not good when the c5-pawn has been exchanged.} ({In the next example features
Black's most principled option -} 9... Bf5) 10. Qb3 Qxb3 {Having played ...Qb6,
it's difficult to refrain from exchanging queens. Otherwise, in many cases,
Black should reckon with Qxb6 followed by Bc7. Even without Bc7, however,
Black's b6-pawn would be quite vulnerable.} 11. axb3 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gb1d2,
Gb3b4,Gb4b5,Ga1a3,Gf1a1] White is now ready to proceed with his typical plan -
Nbd2 and b3-b4-b5 followed by doubling the rooks along the a-file. He should
only watch for a counterplay based on ...e7-e5.} a6 12. Nbd2 Bd7 13. Rfe1 Nd8 {
[%cal Gd8e6,Gd7b5] Black's plan becomes clear. He wants to proceed with ...Ne6
followed by ...Bb5. Nevertheless, this creative approach does not solve the
problems.} 14. b4 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gb3c5] White is planning to get his knight to
c5. The next few moves are quite logical.} Ne6 15. Be5 Bb5 16. Nb3 Bxe2 17.
Rxe2 Ne4 18. Nc5 N6xc5 19. bxc5 {[%csl Gb6,Rb7] The modification of the pawn
structure is favourable for White. The c5-pawn gives a lot of space on the
queenside. In the future, White can make use of the weak b6-square and the
backward b7-pawn. In some cases, Black should reckon with the advance b2-b4-b5.
} Rfc8 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Ne5 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ge5d3] It's time to chase away the
slightly annoying black knight. Besides preparing the advance f2-f3, White
also transfers his knight to d3.} Rc7 22. f3 Ng3 23. Ree1 Re8 24. Kf2 Nh5 25.
Nd3 e6 26. Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d5] Threatening Nxd5.} Nf4 $2 {This move loses on the
spot. The position, however, is already difficult. Had Black played something
else, White could have started gaining space on the kingside with the idea to
create new weaknesses.} 27. g3 $1 Nxh3+ 28. Kg2 Ng5 29. Nxd5 Rcc8 30. Nb6 Rcd8
31. f4 $18 {White is winning a piece.} e5 32. fxg5 exd4 33. Rxe8 Rxe8 34. cxd4
Re2+ 35. Kf3 Rxb2 36. d5 Rb3+ 37. Kf4 Rb4+ 38. Ke5 Kf8 39. Nd7+ Ke7 40. Nf6 Rb2
41. d6+ Kd8 42. Re1 1-0

