{[%evp 0,107,30,14,27,27,27,27,35,35,41,9,22,22,14,24,17,28,14,16,25,30,47,36,
36,13,55,55,43,40,41,27,41,33,43,41,40,6,50,17,-3,-3,21,6,6,13,23,35,52,29,24,
38,43,36,35,41,36,4,14,36,-3,-3,17,2,6,26,37,30,65,-1,0,-17,-12,-39,-45,-4,36,
34,54,54,67,76,75,23,65,75,75,75,75,75,75,75,92,93,117,106,101,119,131,134,129,
102,233,256,256,341,346,346,476,497] Even though the next example is a blitz
game, it's highly instructive both from theoretical and positional point of
view. After the moves} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 d5 3. Bf4 g6 4. e3 Bg7 5. Be2 O-O 6. h3
c5 7. O-O cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6 9. c3 {Instead of 9...Qb6, Black played the optimal}
Bf5 {developing the bishop and getting ready to answer 10.Nbd2 with 10...Ne4.
After playing ...Ne4, Black will be trying to somehow prepare the advance ...
e7-e5. As we are going to see, however, this is not an easy task.} 10. Nbd2 Ne4
11. Re1 {When playing this structure, before doing anything else, always try
to put a rook on e1. This rook puts pressure along the e-file and makes it
difficult for Black to carry out ...e7-e5.} Nxd2 {The idea is to make the
e4-square available for the bishop. The game shows that this idea does not
work quite well.} ({It is very important to remember that the move} 11... f6 {
[%cal Ge7e5] planning ...e7-e5 should always be met with} 12. c4 $1 {
Immediately attacking Black's centre. This idea can be seen in different
classical opening such as Nimzo-Indian Defence and Queen's Gambit Declined.}
Nxd2 13. Qxd2 $14 {White keeps an edge due to his active pieces and pressure
along the e-file.}) ({One can ask himself how should White proceed, provided
that Black does nothing concrete. I believe the following sequence
demonstrates some of White's important ideas.} 11... h6 12. Bh2 g5 13. Qb3 Qd7
14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Nd2 Bf5 16. Qb5 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gb3c5] followed by Nb3-c5
with an annoying pressure on the queenside. The exchange on e4 followed by the
manoeuvre Nf3-d2-b3-c5 is thematic for such positions. Remember it.}) 12. Qxd2
Be4 $6 {The bishop proves to be unstable here. On the other hand, in such
positions, Black's main problem is that at some point he runs out of
constructive ideas. Meanwhile, White will combine his kingside play with
pressure along the e-file.} 13. Ng5 $1 Bf5 14. Bf1 {There is nothing wrong
with this typical move.} ({Another option would have been} 14. g4 Bd7 15. Nf3 {
[%cal Ge2d3,Gg1g2,Ge1e8] White can proceed with Bd3 followed by Kg2. Later on,
he can double the rooks on the e-file and start a kingside attack by
exchanging the dark-squared bishops via h6.}) 14... Re8 15. g4 Bd7 16. Bg2 {
This was the point behind White's previous play. By provoking the advance ...
e7-e6, he forces the black light-squared bishop behind the central pawn chain.}
e6 17. Nf3 Na5 18. Ne5 Rc8 19. Bh6 $6 {I believe White shouldn't have rushed
with this move.} ({More precise would have been} 19. b3 {Stopping all ...
Nc4-based ideas.}) 19... Nc4 20. Nxc4 Rxc4 21. Bxg7 $6 {This exchange makes
Black's defence easier. With a king on g7, Black can try ...Rh8 followed by ...
h7-h5. Later on, after mutual inaccuracies (typical for a blitz game), White
managed to win.} ({White should have played} 21. Bg5 Bf6 22. h4 $40 {with
annoying attack.}) 21... Kxg7 22. g5 b5 (22... Rh8 $1 {[%cal Gh7h6]} 23. Qf4 h6
24. h4 hxg5 25. hxg5 Rh5 $11) 23. a3 a5 24. Qf4 Kg8 25. h4 Qc7 26. Qf6 Qd8 27.
Qe5 Qc7 28. Qf6 Qd8 29. Qf3 (29. Bf1 Qxf6 30. gxf6 Rc7 31. h5 Kf8 32. Bd3 Rec8
33. Kg2 $16) 29... b4 30. axb4 axb4 31. Bf1 Rc8 32. cxb4 Qb6 33. Qf6 Qxb4 34.
h5 Qe7 35. Qxe7 $2 (35. Ra7 $18) 35... Rxe7 36. h6 Be8 37. b4 Rb8 38. b5 Reb7
39. Reb1 Kf8 40. Ra5 Ke7 41. Kh2 Rb6 42. Kg3 Kd6 43. Kf4 Bd7 44. Bd3 R8b7 45.
Ra6 Rb8 46. Rba1 Ke7 47. Rxb6 Rxb6 48. Ke5 Rb7 49. Rb1 Rb6 50. Rb2 Rb7 51. b6
Bc6 52. Ba6 Rb8 53. b7 Bd7 54. Rc2 1-0

