{[%evp 0,83,22,13,13,13,27,30,57,26,17,12,24,36,43,20,40,23,28,25,17,-8,-8,5,
19,14,23,14,17,16,10,-19,-14,-21,-21,-13,-18,-18,-17,-13,-19,-21,-7,-7,0,0,1,
-8,12,0,31,31,29,31,31,31,23,18,23,23,38,20,23,23,29,18,23,10,11,0,46,49,27,19,
47,39,146,151,151,153,148,156,145,151,2405,2841] At the end of the lecture, I
would like to take a look at an idea which does not fit into neither of the
pawn structures examined so far - weakening and utilizing the b5-square. I
would illustrate this idea with a model game of Boris Grachev. We are quite
familiar with the first 12 moves -} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5.
Nd2 g6 6. Ngf3 Bg7 7. h3 O-O 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Ne5 {Just a reminder. By
exchanging the c6-knight, White makes possible the thematic advance a2-a4-a5.}
Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Qd7 12. a4 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga4a5,Ga5b6,Ga7b6,Gd1b3] This is the
point. White's plan is simple - create a weakness on b6 by means of a4-a5
followed by axb6 and attack it with Qb3. Therefore, Black played} a5 {
weakening the b5-square. At this point, Grachev finds a very instructive way
to use the b5-square. After exchanging the light-squared bishops with} 13. Bb5
Bc6 14. Bxc6 Qxc6 {he played the subtle} 15. Nb1 $1 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gb1a3,
Ga3b5] transferring the knight to b5. This is a thematic manoeuvre when the
moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 are included.} Nd7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Na3 e5 18. Nb5
Rad8 19. Qb3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga1d1,Gb3d5,Gd1d5] Once again, we see this
typical idea. White is planning to put indirect pressure on d5 by means of
Rad1. The idea is to force Black to release the tension in the centre.} Rfe8
20. Rad1 exd4 21. exd4 c4 22. Qc2 {This symmetrical pawn structure is
favourable for White. White's advantage is based on 3 main factors: 1) more
active knight 2) vulnerable d5-pawn 3) possibility to initiate a queenside
play by means of b2-b3} Nf6 23. Rfe1 Re6 24. Re5 Nd7 $6 {This move is quite
passive.} ({Black should have tried} 24... Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6] with the idea of
exchanging the b5-knight by means of ...Nd6. Even though White keeps a slight
edge, the position is close to equal.}) 25. Rxe6 Qxe6 26. Qd2 {[%cal Gd1e1] It
turns out that Black cannot fight for the e-file since 26...Re8? runs into 27.
Nc7, winning an exchange.} Nf6 27. Re1 Qd7 28. Qf4 Re8 29. Re5 {The difference
in the piece activity becomes obvious.} Re6 30. f3 {Played on general grounds.
The idea is to restrict the f6-knight.} ({In my opinion, more energetic would
have been} 30. Rxe6 Qxe6 31. Nc7 Qe1+ ({Funny enough} 31... Qe7 $2 {loses to
the elegant} 32. Qxf6+ $1 $18 {with a fork to follow.}) 32. Kh2 {Black is
under pressure.}) 30... Nh5 31. Qe3 Nf6 {Black does not have constructive
ideas. Even though the computer holds this position, for a human it's not easy
at all. Especially in fast time controls.} 32. g4 Qe7 33. Rxe6 Qxe6 34. Kf2 $6
{Allowing Black to consolidate.} ({The favourable way to exchange the queens
would have been} 34. Qxe6 fxe6 35. Na7 Nd7 36. Nc6 Kf6 37. f4 $16 {with a
better knight endgame.}) 34... Nd7 $2 {This mistake leads to a lost position.}
({After} 34... Qxe3+ 35. Kxe3 Ne8 36. Kf4 f6 $11 {Black should be able to hold
the knight endgame.}) 35. Nc7 $6 {The severe time-trouble leads to
inaccuracies.} ({The best is} 35. Qf4 {transposing to the game.}) 35... Qc6 36.
Nb5 Qe6 $2 ({Black should play} 36... Qf6 {stopping Qf4.}) 37. Qf4 $18 Qe7 38.
Nc7 Qh4+ 39. Qg3 Qg5 40. f4 Qe7 41. Qe3 Qd6 42. Ne8+ 1-0

