{[#] Now, we shall take a look at a short fragment that illustrates how to
handle the Exchange Slav structure with a bishop on g7. As pointed out in the
introduction, this structure is favourable for White because of the difference
in the activity of the dark-squared bishops. This game is a model for what
White should aim for. The plan of taking control over the c-file is easy and
straightforward, while Black is short of any positive defensive ideas.} 18. Nb5
$1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc1c8] Black needs good advice as he is losing control
over the c-file and the g7-bishop is just a mere spectator.} Rxc2 ({From this
moment onward} 18... a6 {was never possible because of} 19. Nc7 $18) 19. Rxc2
Bf8 20. Rc3 $1 h5 21. a3 Qd8 22. Qc2 Ba6 ({After} 22... Nd6 {White can invade
the c-file by means of} 23. Nxd6 Bxd6 24. Bxd6 Qxd6 25. Rc7 {The problem is
that} Rb8 {loses to} 26. Rxb7 Rxb7 27. Qc8+ $18) ({On the other hand,} 22...
Kh7 {runs into} 23. Bxg6+ fxg6 24. Nc7 $18) 23. Qa4 $1 {getting the bishop
pair.} Bxb5 (23... Bb7 24. Nc7 $18) 24. Bxb5 Nd6 25. Bc6 (25. Ba6 b5 26. Bxb5
$18) 25... Rc8 26. Qxa7 {Winning a pawn. Black's counterplay is insufficient.}
Ne4 27. Rc2 g5 28. Be5 f6 (28... Bd6 29. Bxd6 Nxd6 30. Ba4 $18) 29. Bh2 g4 30.
hxg4 hxg4 31. Bf4 Bd6 32. Bxd6 Qxd6 33. Ba4 Rxc2 34. Bxc2 Ng5 35. Qb7 f5 36.
Ba4 g3 37. f4 Ne4 38. Qc8+ Kg7 39. Bd7 Qe7 40. Bxe6 Nf6 41. b4 b5 42. Kh1 Ng4
43. Qd7 Qxd7 44. Bxd7 Nxe3 45. Bxb5 Kf6 46. a4 Ke7 47. a5 Kd8 48. Ba4 Kc7 49.
Kg1 Kc8 50. Bc6 Kb8 51. b5 Kc7 52. Be8 Nc4 53. Bf7 Ne3 54. Be6 Kd6 55. b6 Kc6
56. Bc8 Nc2 57. b7 Kc7 58. a6 Kb8 59. Bxf5 Nb4 60. Be6 *

