{[#]} 16... c4 $1 {This is the most precise continuation. Whenever you have
doubled pawns on the a-file, you should try to fix the b2-pawn by means of ...
c5-c4. Computer analysis shows that the weaknesses of a5 and b2 would
compensate each other.} 17. Bc2 Bc6 18. Qa3 Ra7 {At this point, critical would
have been} 19. Rfb1 {when the following sequence illustrates the character of
the play:} ({The game saw} 19. Ne5 Bb5 20. Qxa5 Rb7 {when Black was doing fine.
}) 19... a4 20. Nd2 a5 21. Bxa4 Bxa4 22. Qxa4 Qa6 23. Ra3 Rc8 24. Rba1 Rca8 25.
Qc2 Qb5 26. b3 cxb3 27. Qxb3 Qxb3 28. Nxb3 Ne4 $11 {The position is equal.}
1/2-1/2

