{[%evp 0,70,25,26,18,14,13,18,53,13,-1,-17,17,19,14,23,47,-8,-19,-34,-30,-34,
-42,-141,-54,-50,-16,-44,-36,-46,-34,-47,8,-7,-7,-46,-59,-59,-79,-56,24,-21,
-24,-53,-17,-33,-33,-27,-37,-57,-8,-72,-72,-74,-92,-74,-74,-80,-74,-111,-92,
-240,-149,-200,-168,-182,-212,-250,-241,-241,-146,-324,-398]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
d5 3. Bf4 g6 {Compared to the usual London system positions, the knight is not
placed so well on the c3-square as on d2 in some lines. White has two main
ideas in this type of position: 1) to push h2-h4-h5, usually supported by Be2,
and 2) to play Nb5 trying to gain some tempi on the queenside. In this game,
we will see a third option, a relatively rare move} 4. Qd2 $6 {In principle,
this is a reasonable move, preparing Bh6 and possibly f3-e4, as well (as in
the Veresov variation). However, I think that it is objectively not so good
for White because he does not seem to be fully ready for the opening of the
centre once Black plays...c7-c5.} Bg7 5. h4 {An interesting approach,
preventing Black from castling.} ({In the case of} 5. f3 $6 {[#] the most
natural and best reply is} c5 $1 {trying to open the centre} 6. dxc5 {White
should probably take the pawn.} ({The position is concrete and we need to know
what to play if White goes} 6. Nb5 $6 {[#]} O-O $1 {We can ignore White's
threat. The point is that after} 7. Nc7 cxd4 8. Nxa8 Nc6 {Black will push e5
and the knight will get trapped.} 9. O-O-O e5 10. Bg5 Qd6 $17 {[%cal Gc8d7]}) (
6. e3 {is harmless} O-O {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 6... Nc6 {Black is now ready to push ..
.d4 or ...e5.} 7. e4 $6 {is a dubious approach, especially when White castles
queenside.} ({Probably the safest choice is} 7. e3 {although Black is
completely fine after} O-O 8. O-O-O Qa5 ({or} 8... e5 $5 9. Bg5 d4 10. exd4
exd4 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. fxe4 Qe8 $132) 9. Kb1 Qxc5 10. Na4 (10. Nxd5 $2 {[#] is
wrong on the account of} Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Rd8 12. Qxd8+ Nxd8 13. Rxd8+ Bf8 14. Bh6
Bf5 $19) 10... Qa5 11. Qxa5 Nxa5 $11) (7. O-O-O d4 $17) 7... d4 8. Nb5 O-O 9.
O-O-O e5 {Black has a very strong center.} 10. Bg5 Be6 11. Kb1 b6 $1 $17 {
A strong idea and thematic pawn sacrifice to open files on the queenside.} 12.
cxb6 Qxb6 13. c4 a6 14. Na3 Rfb8 15. Ka1 Nd7 16. Rb1 Nc5 17. Ne2 Bf8 18. Nc1
Rb7 19. Bh6 Be7 20. Bd3 Rab8 21. Nc2 Na5 22. Qe2 Nxd3 23. Nxd3 Bxc4 24. Qd2
Bxa2 25. b4 Bxb1 26. Rxb1 Nc4 {0-1 (26) Dlugy,M (2518)-Dominguez Perez,L (2732)
Berlin 2015}) (5. O-O-O $6 {[#] is another risky move for White, but we should
change our plan.} c6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (5... c5 $6 {does not work now because
after} 6. dxc5 {the pawn on d5 is hanging in a better version for White.}) 6.
f3 (6. Bh6 Bxh6 7. Qxh6 b5 $1 {[%cal Gd8a5,Gb5b4]} 8. f3 Qa5 9. a3 Na6 $17)
6... b5 $1 7. Kb1 (7. e4 $6 {does not work now because of} b4 8. Na4 dxe4 9.
Qxb4 Nd5 10. Qd2 O-O $17 11. fxe4 Nxf4 12. Qxf4 Qa5 $36) 7... Nbd7 $1 {[%cal
Gd7b6] An important plan - the knight goes to b6 and covers important squares
like c4 and a4.} (7... b4 8. Na4 Qa5 9. Nc5 {is much less clear.}) 8. Bh6 (8.
e4 b4 $17) 8... Bxh6 9. Qxh6 Nb6 10. e4 (10. e3 b4 11. Nce2 a5 $132 {[%cal
Ga5a4]}) 10... b4 11. Nxd5 cxd5 (11... Nfxd5 12. exd5 Qxd5 13. Qg7 Rf8 14. Ne2
a5 15. Nf4 Qd6 $13) 12. e5 Nfd7 13. e6 (13. Qg7 Rf8) 13... fxe6 14. Qg7 Rf8 15.
Qxh7 Qc7 16. Qxg6+ Kd8 $17) (5. Bh6 {is a reasonable alternative. I would
prefer} O-O {before playing ...c5. White's main idea is to attack with} 6. h4 (
6. Bxg7 Kxg7 7. O-O-O c5 8. e3 (8. dxc5 Qa5 9. Nxd5 Qxa2 10. Qc3 Be6 11. Nxf6
exf6 12. Nf3 Nd7 13. Nd4 Rfd8 14. e3 Rac8 15. c6 Ne5 16. Qa3 Qxa3 17. bxa3 Nxc6
$15) 8... c4 $5 $146 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (8... Nc6 $6 9. dxc5 Qa5 10. Bb5) (8... Qa5
$5 9. Kb1 Nc6) 9. e4 b5 $1 10. e5 Ng8 11. h4 b4 12. Nce2 Nc6 13. h5 (13. c3 Qa5
14. Kb1 Rb8 15. Ka1 Rb6 $19) 13... c3 14. bxc3 Qa5 $17) (6. O-O-O c5) 6... c5 {
We typically rely on this move for counterplay against White's kingside attack.
} 7. Bxg7 Kxg7 8. e3 (8. h5 $6 {looks attractive for White, but he has no real
threats and Black can open the centre with} cxd4 9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qh4 d4 $17 11.
hxg6 fxg6 12. Qh6+ Kg8 13. O-O-O Qa5 14. Ne4 Rf7 $17) 8... cxd4 (8... Nc6 $5 {
is also possible, but sharper}) 9. exd4 h5 {This is the simplest solution for
Black. White's attack has been slowed down considerably.} 10. O-O-O (10. Bd3
Nc6 11. Nge2 Nb4 12. Nf4 Qb6 13. Nce2 Nxd3+ 14. cxd3 (14. Nxd3 Bf5 $15) 14...
Bf5 15. Ng3 e6 $15 {1/2-1/2 (48) Naroditsky,D (2646)-Shankland,S (2674) chess.
com INT 2017}) 10... Nc6 11. f3 Bf5 $132 {Black is getting ready to attack on
the c-file.}) 5... h5 {This is the most solid reply.} ({A sharper alternative} 
5... c5 $5 6. e3 Nc6 {is also playable.}) 6. e3 O-O {White cannot play Bh6 any
more, so Qd2 move becomes superfluous for White.} 7. Nf3 c5 8. dxc5 Nbd7 $1 {
This is how Black plans to recoup the pawn. The point is that there is no good
way for White to capture the d5-pawn.} 9. Bd3 (9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Qxd5 Bxb2 $19)
(9. O-O-O Nxc5 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Qb6 12. Be5 Be6 13. Qd2 Rfd8 14. Qe1 Bxe5
15. Rxd8+ Rxd8 16. Nxe5 Bxa2 $17) 9... Nxc5 10. O-O-O Bg4 $17 {Black got an
easy game - White had no attack.} 11. Kb1 a6 12. Be5 b5 13. a3 Rc8 14. Qe2 Nxd3
$6 (14... Ncd7 $1 $19) 15. cxd3 (15. Rxd3 $142) 15... b4 16. axb4 Qb6 17. Bxf6
Qxf6 18. Nxd5 Qd6 19. e4 Bd4 (19... e6 $17) 20. Rc1 e6 21. Ne3 Bxf3 22. gxf3
Qxb4 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Nc4 a5 25. Qc2 a4 26. Ka2 e5 27. Rg1 Rc5 28. Rg5 Kg7 29.
f4 exf4 30. e5 Rb5 31. e6 fxe6 32. Rxb5 Qxb5 33. Qe2 Qb3+ 34. Kb1 e5 35. Qf3 a3
0-1

