1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 g6 4. e3 {This is the main move.} Bg7 5. Nb5 {
Grischuk's favorite.} ({Another plan is} 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 {It seems passive
for White, but it was played by Magnus Carlsen recently, so it deserves
attention.} c5 {Once again, this is the most natural continuation.} 7. O-O (7.
dxc5 {This is probably the best option.} Nbd7 $5 {This should be preferred} ({
over} 7... Qa5) 8. O-O (8. Nxd5 {is also possible, since after} Nxd5 9. Qxd5
Bxb2 {White can sacrifice an exchange with} 10. O-O Bxa1 11. Rxa1 {[#] White
definitely has compensation for the sacrificed material. The most practical
solution is to give back the exchange with} Qa5 12. Bh6 Qxc5 13. Qb3 (13. Qxc5
$6 Nxc5 14. Bxf8 Kxf8 $15) 13... b6 14. Rd1 Nf6 15. Bxf8 Kxf8 $11 {as played
in the game 0-1 (31) Sriram,J (2388)-Ganguly,S (2650) Bhubaneswar 2018}) 8...
Nxc5 9. Be5 b6 $5 {is a nice pawn sacrifice. After} 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Qxd5 Bb7
12. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $44 {and Black has a fantastic compensation thanks to the
bishop pair. The knight on c3 is particularly awkwardly placed.} 13. Nd1 $6
Rac8 14. Rc1 (14. c3 e5) 14... Nd3 15. Bxd3 Rxd3 16. cxd3 Rxc1 17. d4 Rc2 $17 {
0-1 (50) Blatny,P (2495)-Wojtkiewicz,A (2540) Corfu 1991}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 {
White's play in the opening was not ambitious and Black has several good
options already.} Bg4 {preparing to swap the light-squared bishops.} ({or} 8...
Nc6 9. Ne5 Bf5 10. Nxc6 bxc6 $11) 9. h3 (9. Ne5 Bxe2 10. Nxe2 Qb6 $11) 9...
Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nc6 11. Ne2 b5 12. c3 e6 {Black seems to be doing very well in
the reversed Carlsbad structure because he has a simple minority attack on the
queenside while white bishop pair is ineffective. Black position already looks
slightly more promising.} 13. a3 a5 14. Nc1 b4 15. a4 (15. Nd3 bxc3 16. bxc3
Ne4 17. Rc1 $11) 15... Ne4 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Nb3 e5 18. dxe5 bxc3 19. bxc3 Nxe5
20. Bxe5 Bxe5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (85) Carlsen,M (2837)-Ding,L (2774) Saint Louis 2017
}) 5... Na6 {White's idea was to misplace the knight on a6, so that Black has
a more difficult time centralizing it.} 6. Nf3 ({I believe that} 6. h3 $5 {
is more accurate as it prevents Bg4 pin and clears h2-square for the bishop 
(in case of Nh5).} O-O 7. Nf3 {This is one of the critical positions in this
system.} Ne4 $5 {The most aggressive option. The idea is to discourage white
knight from retreating to c3.} (7... c6 8. Nc3 Nc7 (8... c5 {is not the same
as in other lines because the knight is placed worse on the rim than on c6.})
9. Bd3 Nce8 $5 {This is a better idea than 9...Ne6, with the following
maneuver in mind:} 10. O-O Nd6 11. Re1 Bf5 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Qe2 Nfe4 $11 {
1-0 (38) Alekseenko,K (2696)-Iljiushenok,I (2516) chess.com INT 2020}) 8. Nd2 {
It makes a lot of sense to try to immediately exchange the strong knight.} (8.
c3 {[#]} f6 $1 {This is the best plan for Black. The e5-break can be played
without additional preparation since f2-pawn is hanging.} ({The idea behind 8.
c3 is that after} 8... c6 9. Na3 Qb6 {he can protect the b2-pawn with} 10. Qb3)
9. Be2 c6 10. Na3 e5 {White cannot take on e5, so} 11. Bh2 {is forced. Black
has many options, but the simplest one seems to be} exd4 12. Nxd4 {This may be
the best option for White.} (12. exd4 Nc7 13. O-O Ne6 $132 {[%cal Gf6f5,Gg6g5]}
) ({The point is that after} 12. cxd4 Qa5+ $1 13. Nd2 c5 $132 {[%cal Gf6f5] is
unplesant for White.}) 12... Nc7 13. O-O f5 14. Nb1 Ne6 15. Nd2 $11 {Both
sides have improved their knights. Although the position seems about equal, I
prefer Black slightly because of the space advantage.}) (8. Be2 c6 9. Na3 {
Now white knight is not placed well either.} (9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qa5 {
is not a good structure for White.}) 9... Qb6 10. Qc1 Bf5 11. O-O c5 12. c3
Rac8 $132 {Black has very good chances here.}) 8... c6 $5 {I prefer this move}
({over} 8... Nxd2 9. Qxd2 c6 10. Nc3 Nc7 11. Be2 $6 (11. Bh2 Ne8 $5 (11... Re8
12. Bd3 e5 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Rxe5 15. O-O-O {[%cal Gh3h4,Gh4h5]} b5 16. h4
$13) 12. Bd3 Nd6 13. O-O (13. O-O-O $6 b5 $1) 13... Re8 14. Rfe1 e5 15. dxe5
Bxe5 16. Bxe5 Rxe5 17. e4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Qe7 19. Bd3 Bf5 $11) 11... Ne6 $1 12.
Be5 (12. Bg3 c5 $1) 12... Bxe5 13. dxe5 d4 (13... Qc7 $5 14. f4 Rd8) 14. exd4
Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Nxd4 16. Bd3 Rd8 17. O-O-O Be6 $11 {0-1 (63) Tabatabaei,M (2306)
-Gupta,A (2562) Hamedan 2018}) {White needs to enter a forced line:} 9. Nxe4
dxe4 10. Nc3 c5 {Black is trying to open the center.} 11. Be5 {1/2-1/2 (78)
Perelshteyn,E (2493)-Mikhalevski,V (2574) Saint Louis 2018} ({Black has a nice
position with the bishop pair after} 11. Bxa6 cxd4 12. exd4 bxa6 13. Ne2 Qb6
$11) ({Another option is} 11. Nxe4 cxd4 12. exd4 {[#]} Qd5 $1 {This is the
best option since white pieces are vulnerable.} ({White gets a better endgame
in the case of} 12... Qxd4 $6 13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. O-O-O) 13. Nc3 Qf5 14. Be3 Nb4
{The knight gets into the game with a tempo. Black has a strong initiative.}
15. Rc1 Rd8 $44) {This is the safest option for White, but Black is not worse
at all after} 11... Bxe5 12. dxe5 Qb6 13. Qc1 (13. Nd5 Qxb2 {[%cal Gb2e5]})
13... Qc7 14. Nxe4 Qxe5 $11) 6... Bg4 $5 (6... O-O 7. h3 {transposes to 6.h3} (
7. Be2 {gives Black an additional option} Nh5 $5 8. Bg5 f6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 c6
11. Nc3 e5 $132)) 7. Be2 (7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 c6 9. Nc3 Qa5) 7... c6 8. Nc3 Qb6
9. Rb1 Nd7 {Black is getting ready to push ...e5 at the right moment.} 10. O-O
O-O (10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 $11) 11. e4 {White plays in the
center first, but this weakens the d4-pawn.} e6 {A solid approach. Of course,
Black has no problems in this type of position.} ({I would prefer a more
direct continuation} 11... dxe4 $5 12. Nxe4 Rad8 {with a pressure against
d4-pawn. Black is ready to carry out one of the central breaks.}) 12. Be3 Rfd8
13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nc7 15. Qd2 Nb5 $1 {Solving the problem of misplaced
knight.} 16. Nxb5 Qxb5 17. c3 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Nb6 $11 {The arising position is
approximately equal because White's bishop pair is not effective.} 19. Qc2 Nc4
20. Qb3 Qxb3 21. axb3 Nxe3 22. fxe3 a5 23. Ra1 e5 24. Ra4 f5 25. Bf3 h5 26.
Rfa1 Bh6 27. Kf2 e4 28. Be2 f4 29. exf4 Bxf4 30. Rxa5 Rxa5 31. Rxa5 Bc1 32. Re5
Bxb2 33. Rxe4 Bxc3 34. Ke3 Kf8 35. Bc4 Re8 36. Rxe8+ Kxe8 37. Ke4 Ke7 38. d5
cxd5+ 39. Bxd5 b6 40. Bc4 Kf6 41. Bd3 Bb4 42. Bc2 Bc5 1/2-1/2

