{[%evp 0,61,18,27,27,27,39,33,36,28,39,11,22,29,36,16,19,29,37,30,26,33,36,35,
34,43,41,29,28,32,112,99,115,58,63,65,61,49,62,50,60,44,70,71,105,51,64,61,80,
36,72,52,59,59,52,55,155,147,138,133,313,160,545,743]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3.
Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 $5 h5 {Once again, this is probably the best response
to White's h-pawn attack.} (5... c5 $6 {[#] is now premature because of} 6. Nb5
$1 O-O $6 (6... Na6 {is more solid, but then White is just positionally better
after} 7. Be2 O-O 8. c3 Bd7 9. a4 $14 {because the knight on b5 can never be
kicked-out and Na6 is poorly placed.}) 7. Nc7 Nh5 8. Bh2 cxd4 {we saw a
similar idea before, where Black sacrifices an exchange for better development,
but here it is simply not working for Black due to:} 9. exd4 Nc6 10. Nxa8 e5
11. dxe5 $1 {This is the most accurate move.} (11. Be2 $6 Nxd4 12. Bxh5 gxh5
13. c3 Nc6 14. Qxh5 Be6 15. Nf3 f6 16. Nd2 Qxa8 17. O-O Qc8 (17... f5 $44) 18.
Qf3 f5 19. Nb3 b6 20. Rfe1 f4 $13 {1-0 (39) Alekseenko,K (2704)-Ivanisevic,I 
(2593) Moscow RUS 2019}) 11... Nxe5 12. Be2 $16 {White is ready to complete
development with Nf3, 0-0, preserving the material advantage.}) (5... a6 $6 {
prevents Nb5, but it is probably just a waste of time for Black.} 6. Nf3 (6.
Be2 $5 h5 7. Nf3) 6... Bg4 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. Ne5 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 c6 10. O-O-O h5 11.
e4 (11. f3 $5 {[%cal Ge3e4]}) 11... dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 14. Qd3 Qd5
15. Kb1 Qe4 (15... Qxg2 16. Qb3) 16. Qb3 O-O (16... Nd5 17. g3) 17. Bg5 b5 18.
f3 Qd5 19. Qe3 (19. Rhe1 $1) 19... Rfe8 20. g4 Rad8 21. a3 c5 $6 (21... Qe6)
22. dxc5 Qxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 24. Ka2 Nd5 25. Qe2 $18 Rh1 26. gxh5 e6 27. h6
Bh8 28. c6 b4 29. axb4 Nxb4+ 30. Kb3 Nd5 31. Nd7 Rc8 32. c4 Nb6 33. Nxb6 Rb8
34. c5 Rb1 35. c7 {1-0 (35) Alekseenko,K (2696)-Pert,R (2416) chess.com INT
2020}) (5... O-O {also looks dubious in the view of} 6. Nb5 Na6 7. h5 $1 {
and White is getting ready to sacrifice an exchange should Black take on h5.}
c6 (7... Nxh5 8. Rxh5 gxh5 9. Qxh5 $44 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gf1d3]}) 8. Nc3 Nxh5 $6 9.
Rxh5 gxh5 10. Qxh5 $44 {Black king is exposed and White has an easy plan to
attack.}) 6. Nf3 c6 $1 {Black has several other options, but this one should
be the best. This stops Nb5 and allows Black to remain flexible until White
shows his hand.} (6... Bg4 {[#] seems natural, but it is risky because of} 7.
Qd2 $1 {and after} Bxf3 $6 8. gxf3 {White easily pushes e3-e4.} c6 9. O-O-O
Nbd7 10. Kb1 e6 11. e4 $16 {White had an easy game in Bauer,C (2625)-Maze,S 
(2620)/chess.com INT 2018/The Week in Chess 1213 (61)}) ({In the case of} 6...
O-O {White goes} 7. Nb5 (7. Qd2 c5 8. Ne5 Nc6 9. O-O-O Bf5 10. f3 Nb4 $132) {
provoking} 7... Na6 {and after} 8. Ne5 c6 9. Nc3 $14 {Black's problem is that
his knight cannot challenge Ne5 from a6. Also,} Bf5 {is now met with} 10. Bd3 {
owing to the fact that White has not lost a tempo on Be2, as in game 3.}) 7.
Ne5 $6 ({However, I believe that the best move for White is} 7. Be2 $5 O-O {
Not the most popular move, but I believe that Black can obtain good
counter-chances with correct play.} (7... Bg4 8. Ne5 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 {This
position resembles Caruana-Giri game, but an important difference is that
Black does not have the ...Nh5 resource here, so White is better thanks to a
strong control over e5-outpost and active plans like f3-e4/g4.} Nbd7 10. O-O-O
(10. f3 $5) 10... Nxe5 (10... Qa5 $6 11. Kb1 Rc8 12. e4 $40 {1-0 (44) Karjakin,
S (2781)-Giri,A (2771)/Stavanger NOR 2017/The Week in Chess 1178 (44)}) 11.
Bxe5 Qd7 $6 (11... b5 12. f3 Kf8 13. e4 $14) 12. f3 b5 13. e4 a6 14. Kb1 $16 {
1-0 (49) Karjakin,S (2785)-Li Chao2 (2720)/Doha QAT 2016/The Week in Chess
1156 (49)}) (7... Bf5 {is risky due to} 8. Ng5 $1 O-O 9. f3 $36 {[%cal Gg2g4]})
8. Ne5 Nbd7 {It is important to challenge the knight on e5.} 9. Qd2 Nxe5 (9...
Ne4 {does not solve all black problems since after} 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. O-O-O
Nxe5 12. Bxe5 $14 {the e4-pawn is weak.}) 10. Bxe5 b5 {Black needs to create
counter-chances.} (10... Ng4 {is a tempting way to simplify the position, but
White keeps good attacking chances after} 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Bxg4 $5 Bxg4 13. f3
Be6 14. O-O-O $40 {Black king is a bit weak.}) 11. f3 a5 12. O-O-O Qb6 {
This is the best way to keep attacking.} (12... a4 {is premature because of}
13. a3 Qa5 14. Na2 $1 {and White keeps control over b4-square.} Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2
$14 {[%cal Ga2b4] with a pleasant endgame for White.}) 13. Rdg1 (13. g4 a4 14.
Bxf6 $6 Bxf6 15. gxh5 {is a dangerous approach for White. Black's attack is
actually stronger after} b4 16. Nb1 c5 17. hxg6 cxd4 18. Rdg1 b3 $1 19. e4 Qc7
$1 $17) 13... a4 14. g4 (14. a3 {is now met by} b4 15. axb4 a3 $1 16. b3 a2 17.
Kb2 Qxb4 $132 {and here we can see why it was important to start with ...Qb6
before pushing the pawns.}) 14... b4 15. Nd1 {In my view, this is the critical
position of this variation. Objectively, Black should be fine, but his
position is more difficult to play, so precision is needed.} c5 $1 {The best
move, trying to open the position.} (15... b3 {is always met by} 16. a3 $1 hxg4
(16... bxc2 17. Qxc2) 17. h5 $40) 16. gxh5 Nxh5 17. f4 Nf6 {We have a
double-edged position.} 18. h5 $5 (18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. Bd3 (19. Bd4 Qc6 20. Qxb4
Bf5 21. Nc3 a3 $13 22. b3 Rac8) 19... Ne4 20. Bxe4 dxe4 21. h5 b3 22. a3 Bxe5
23. fxe5 Kg7 24. Nc3 Bf5 $11) 18... b3 (18... Ne4 19. Qe1) 19. a3 Ne4 20. Qe1
bxc2 (20... Bf5 $2 21. hxg6 f6 22. Rh8+ $1 Bxh8 23. Qh4 Rf7 (23... Bxg6 24. Bh5
$18) 24. gxf7+ Kxf7 25. Qh5+ Ke6) 21. hxg6 {White needs to sacrifice the
knight.} (21. Nc3 Nxc3 22. Qxc3 cxd4 23. exd4 Bf5 24. hxg6 fxg6 $15) {We enter
a concrete forced line:} 21... cxd1=Q+ 22. Bxd1 fxg6 23. Qh4 Rf6 $1 {The only
defense.} (23... Kf7 24. Rxg6) 24. Bxf6 Qxf6 25. Qh7+ Kf7 26. Rxg6 {White wins
the queen, but Black gets 3 pieces for it.} Qxg6 27. Bh5 Bf5 28. Rg1 Ra6 29.
Bxg6+ Rxg6 30. Qh5 Nf6 31. Qd1 Rxg1 32. Qxg1 cxd4 33. exd4 Bh6 $11) 7... Nbd7
$6 (7... Qb6 $1 {This is a strong improvement for Black, obstructing White's
plan to castle long.} 8. Qc1 (8. b3 {creates too many weaknesses on the
queenside and Black can exploit it with} Ng4 $1 9. Nd3 Bf5 $132 {[%cal Gb8d7,
Ge7e5] preparing to open the center with ...e5.}) (8. Na4 Qa5+) 8... Nbd7 9. f3
Nxe5 10. Bxe5 O-O {White's piece coordination has been compromised and he
cannot castle queenside.} 11. Be2 Ne8 $1 {Black exchanges the last white piece
that controls e5-square and soon prepares the ...e5 break himself.} 12. Bxg7
Nxg7 13. g4 Re8 $15 {[%cal Ge7e5]}) 8. Bd3 {This is the difference compared to
Be2 variations - White can place the bishop on d3 in one go.} (8. f3 $5) 8...
Nf8 {Carlsen won convincingly after Black's passive play.} 9. Qd2 Ne6 10. Bg3
Nd7 11. Nf3 b5 12. Ne2 Nb6 13. O-O O-O 14. b3 Nc4 15. bxc4 bxc4 16. Rfc1 cxd3
17. cxd3 $16 c5 18. Rab1 cxd4 19. Nexd4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Bd7 21. Rb7 e5 22. Nc6
Bxc6 23. Rxc6 a5 24. Rcc7 Qf6 25. Rd7 Qc6 26. Rbc7 Qb6 27. Qc2 d4 28. exd4 Rae8
29. Qc4 Re6 30. d5 Ree8 31. d6 1-0

