{[%evp 0,49,30,30,30,23,35,35,35,6,29,29,42,18,19,11,11,-1,7,7,-10,-8,8,2,-5,
-16,3,3,1,0,14,15,15,19,16,19,190,189,189,116,149,116,184,179,178,178,181,152,
159,120,311,298] In this lecture I will untroduce you several middlegame
positions without queens in the London System with g6. I divide them in 3
categories: 1.Endgame with an open "d" file. 2.Black is exchanging queens on
"b3" 3.White is exchanging queens on "b6" We will start with the first one. In
the next game, Kamsky exchanged the queens on move eight and won a nice game
for just 25 moves.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. h3 {Kamsky
chooses an interesting move order. Usually, White is playing h3 when Black
chooses the plan with d6-e5.} d6 (5... c5 {is critical here}) 6. e3 c5 7. dxc5
$5 dxc5 {and was unsurprisingly happy to remove the queens:} 8. Qxd8 $5 {
A pet line of Gata Kamsky. White has an initiative in the endgame. Black's
queenside is weakened, and the bishop on "h2" is a monster. On the contrary,
Black's bishop on "g7" is very passive and restricted by the "c3" pawn.} ({
White could also keep the queens by means of} 8. Nbd2) 8... Rxd8 9. Nbd2 Nc6
10. Bc7 Rf8 (10... Rd7 {is the most common move} 11. Bh2 Rd8 12. Bb5 $1 {
Is the best move in my opinion} (12. a4 $6 {Looks too slow} Bf5 13. Bb5 Ne4 14.
g4 $5 Nxd2 15. Nxd2 Be6 {White is risking finding himself in trouble here.
Kamsky-Dobrov, Chicago 2015,}) ({Was tried by Kramnik, but failed to impress
after} 12. Bc4 b6 13. O-O-O Bb7 14. Rhe1 Nd7 15. Kc2 a6 $15 {[%cal Rb6b5,Rd7e5]
0-1 (55) Kramnik,V (2800) -Grischuk,A (2767) Moscow 2018}) 12... Bd7 13. a4 a6
14. Be2 b5 $1 {very good move. Black should stop Nc4, and fortunately for him,
b5 works tactically.} 15. O-O (15. axb5 $2 {opens the "a" file for Black} axb5
16. Rxa8 Rxa8 17. Bxb5 $4 Ra1+ {Black wins}) 15... b4 $6 {Black decides to put
pressure on the "b2" and "c3" pawns and to open the long diagonal, but this
leaves the "c4" square available for the knight.} (15... c4 $1 {was the
correct approach, and now it is not easy for White to make any progress on the
queenside.}) 16. Rac1 (16. cxb4 $1 cxb4 17. Rac1 {was putting more pressure to
Black's position}) 16... Bf5 (16... Nd5 $1 {Black missed a chance to equailize}
17. Ne4 (17. cxb4 Bxb2 {works well here} 18. Rc2 Bc3 19. bxc5 Ncb4 20. Rcc1
Bxd2 21. Nxd2 Bxa4 $11 {And Black should hold this}) 17... bxc3 18. bxc3 c4 $1
{very nice move, fixing the weakness on "c3". After it, massive exchanges will
come, and Black should hold the position.} 19. Bxc4 {runs to} Nb6 20. Bb3 Na5
$11 {and the "a4" pawn will fall}) 17. cxb4 Nxb4 18. Rxc5 Nd3 19. Bxd3 Bxd3 20.
Re1 e6 {The last mistake. This move is too slow and allows White to
consolidate his position.} (20... Nd7 $1 21. Rd5 Bf5 {[%cal Rf5e6]} 22. Nd4 Be6
$14 {White is still better, but it seems that Black has a decent counterplay
on the "b" file. The position remains "Benko" Gambit. Black's pieces are
better coordinated and partly compensate for the missing pawn. I still believe
that White is slightly better, but the position remains playable.}) 21. Nd4 Nd5
22. N2f3 Bf8 23. Rcc1 {The smoke is gone, and now it is clear that Black
doesn't have enough compensation for the missing pawn. Kamsky manages to
convert his material advantage at the end. 1-0 (40) Kamsky,G (2637)-Smirin, I 
(2685) Germany 2016}) 11. Bh2 {The program move, the bishop on "h2" is better
placed than on "f4" so If Black continues with Rd8, White just won half tempo.
Nevertheless, 11...Rd8 is probably the best move in the position.} b6 12. Bb5 {
White is winning a tempo by attacking the knight.} Bb7 13. O-O Rfd8 14. Rfd1 {
The opening is over. We can conclude that White's position is slightly better
and easier to play, but it is hard to imagine that Kamsky can win this only
for 11 moves. White's main plan in such a structure is to push a4-a5. The
other typical idea is to play Nc4 followed by Nfd2-b3 supporting a4-a5 and
putting pressure on "b6" and "c5" pawns. Black's main problem is the lack of
counterplay.} Ne8 (14... a6 $2 {is a typical mistake} 15. Bxc6 $1 Bxc6 16. Nc4
b5 17. Nb6 Rab8 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Bc7 Re8 20. Ne5) (14... Rac8 $1 {was the
best defence} 15. Nc4 (15. a4 {is well met by} Na5 16. Ne5 Ne4 {And Black is
exploiting the weakened "b3" square}) 15... Rxd1+ 16. Rxd1 Rd8 17. Rxd8+ Nxd8 {
the trick is that} 18. Bb8 $2 {is not working} a6 {and Black wins a piece}) (
14... Kf8 15. Be2 {I think that this is just a waste of time. White could
immediately push a4} (15. a4 $1) 15... Rd7 16. a4 Rad8 17. Nc4 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1
Rxd1+ 19. Bxd1 {Another typical endgame for this structure. White always keeps
slightly better chances, mainly because his "h2" bishop is more active than
his "colleague" on "g7," and the pawns on the queenside are vulnerable.} Ne4
20. Bc2 Nf6 21. Nfe5 Nxe5 22. Bxe5 Nd7 23. Bc7 Ke8 (23... Bd5 $1 {should hold
comfortable} 24. Bd3 f5) 24. f3 Bd5 25. Bd3 Bxc4 26. Bxc4 {Later on White
manages to convert his small advantage into a full point. 1-0 (49) Bu,X (2705)
-Grischuk,A (2777) chess24.com INT 2020}) 15. Nc4 f6 16. Nfd2 $1 {Kamsky is a
great master of piece play and continues to maneuver adroitly. His main plan
is now Nb3 followed by a4-a5, but usefully the f-pawn has also been freed for
action. By this stage, I feel safe in saying that White has a definite edge.}
Rd7 $6 (16... e5 {Is well met by} 17. f4 $1) 17. Nb3 Rad8 $2 (17... Rdd8 {
was better defense, but White still keeps the pressure after:} 18. a4) 18. Rxd7
Rxd7 19. a4 $6 {White continues with his plan} ({But much stronger is} 19. Nca5
$1 bxa5 20. Nxc5 Rd2 21. Nxb7 Nd8 22. Nxa5 {with two extra pawns, and if} Nd6
23. Ba4 Rxb2 24. Bb3+ Kf8 25. Bxd6 exd6 26. Nc4 Re2 27. Kf1 {, trapping the
rook.}) 19... e5 20. a5 (20. Nca5 $5 {was both possible and good}) 20... Bf8
21. axb6 axb6 22. Nxb6 Rd8 23. Kf1 Kg7 24. Ke1 Nc7 $2 {was the final mistake
in already lost position} 25. Bxc6 (25. Bxc6 Bxc6 26. Ra7 Bd6 27. Nc4 {wins
apiece.}) 1-0

