{[#] From the same opening like in the previous game we reach this position. I
think understanding this type of positions is very important. We can say that
this is what White is aiming for after the opening. White has an advatage. The
main reason is for that is that Black is totally without counterplay. White
has a very simple plan: Ke2, followed by exchange of one pair of rooks and
then start putting pressure on Black's queenside. Again the difference between
the bishops is crucial.} 16. Nxc4 f6 (16... Nd6 $6 17. Nxd6 exd6 18. O-O-O $18)
(16... b6 17. Ke2 $14 {[%cal Rf3d2,Rh1d1]}) (16... Rac8 17. Ke2 $14) 17. Nfd2 {
The knight is going to b3 trying to provoke "b7-b6" when White can play "a4-a5"
} e5 18. f3 (18. f4 $1 {As we know from the previous example, f2-f4 is
stronger than f2-f3 in this type of positions.} exf4 19. Bxf4 Rd7 20. a5 Rad8
21. O-O-O Bf8 22. Rhf1 $14) 18... Kf7 (18... Bh6 $1 {was better, with the idea}
19. Ke2 Bxd2 $1 20. Nxd2 Nd6 $11) 19. Ke2 Ke6 20. Bg1 Bf8 21. Bf2 Nc7 22. h4 $1
{trying to create weaknesses on the kingside.} b6 (22... h5 {is well met by}
23. g4 $1) 23. h5 g5 {This creates a holl on "f5", but prevents White from
opening the "h" file} 24. Ne3 a6 $2 {this weakens the queenside without a
reason. Black is not in time to push "b6-b5"} (24... Rd7 {with the idea of
doubling the rook was better.}) 25. Ndc4 $1 Rab8 (25... b5 {doesn't work due
to the strong} 26. Nd5 $1 $18) 26. Rhd1 b5 27. Rxd8 Nxd8 28. Na5 c4 29. Nf5
bxa4 30. Nxc4 a3 31. b4 Nb5 32. Be1 Nc6 33. Nxa3 Nxa3 34. Rxa3 a5 {Black
somehow manages to exchange everything on the queenside, but even with pawns
on only one flank White's position remains winning.} 35. Kf2 axb4 36. cxb4 Bxb4
37. Bxb4 Rxb4 38. Ra6 $1 {The pin is annoying but Black's main problem remains
the weaknesses on the kingisde.} Rc4 39. Kg3 Rc3 40. Rb6 Rc2 41. Rb7 h6 42. Rc7
g4 43. Ne3 {An impressive positional achivement by GM Sivuk.} 1-0

