1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. c3 {This is Kamsky's favourite move order.
He preferred to start with this move, keeping the chance to meet "c7-c5" with
"dxc5" followed by "e2-e4"} O-O 5. h3 d6 6. Nbd2 c5 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. e4 Nc6 9.
Be2 Nh5 10. Bh2 e5 {It is hard to suggest anything better here.} 11. Nc4 Nf4 {
An important position for understanding the arising structure. White could be
even worse in this type of position if his knight is misplaced and he couldn't
play Nc4. In this case, Black can start an attack by means of Qf6, Rd8, Nf4,
Be6, etc... In the current position, the knight is already perfectly placed,
and you need to realize that Black has not only one weak square ("d5"), but
two - "d5" and "d6" White achieved an advantage by exploiting the second one.}
12. Bxf4 {First, we need to eliminate the dangerous knight. It may seem that
the "g7" bishop is active now, but this is not true. His power is restricted
by the "c3" pawn.} exf4 13. Qd6 $1 {White forces queen exchange, but in
favourable situation.} Qxd6 14. Nxd6 Rd8 {Black should do something. Otherwise,
Bc4 and Ng5 will come soon.} ({but} 14... Be6 {was better, because the "b7"
pawn is poisoned.} 15. Nxb7 $2 (15. Ng5 Ne5 16. Nxe6 fxe6 {is acceptable for
Black}) 15... Rfb8 16. Nxc5 Rxb2 {Black is much better}) 15. O-O-O Ne5 (15...
Be6 $2 {it is too late for} 16. Nxb7 $18) 16. Rd5 Be6 (16... Nxf3 {doesn't
solve the problems} 17. Bxf3 Bf8 18. e5 $16) 17. Rxe5 Rxd6 (17... Bxe5 18. Nxb7
Rdb8 19. Nxc5) 18. Rxc5 Bxa2 19. Rd1 {Well known idea in such positions is to
exchange a pair of rooks. This reduces Black's dynamic changes.} Rxd1+ 20. Kxd1
Rd8+ 21. Kc2 Be6 22. Ng5 {The main problem for Black is that he can't keep the
bishop on the "a2-g8" diagonal} f3 23. Bxf3 (23. Nxf3 {was better choice})
23... Bc8 (23... Bd7 $1 {with the threat to trap the knight with "f7-f6" or
"h7-h6" next and if White played like in the game} 24. Bg4 $2 {then} (24. e5
$14) 24... Bc6 $1 {and suddenly White's pieces lost coordination and Black is
better.}) 24. Bg4 $1 {leaving Black with his passive dark-squared bishop} Bh6 {
Black decided to transpose into a rook endgame, which is just lost.} 25. Bxc8
Bxg5 26. Rxg5 Rxc8 27. Rd5 {Kamsky had no problems converting the advantage.}
Rc7 28. g4 f6 29. h4 Kf7 30. f4 a6 31. Kd3 Ke7 32. g5 Rc6 33. b4 Rc8 34. c4 Rc6
35. Kd4 Rb6 36. b5 axb5 37. cxb5 Re6 38. e5 f5 39. Kc5 b6+ 40. Kc4 Ke8 41. Rd6
1-0

