{[%evp 0,57,26,37,30,30,44,42,49,26,25,21,24,14,31,37,31,11,27,11,8,18,49,36,
38,27,23,6,31,44,36,42,73,44,46,43,51,50,50,61,54,54,89,99,144,146,163,180,188,
126,149,131,144,144,130,136,136,136,140,137] In this example we will see a
typical Qb3 against Qb6 opposition.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. c3 O-O
5. h3 c5 6. e3 Qb6 7. Qb3 {The opposition of the queens is quite typical for
London system. Usually, both sides are trying not to exchange queens first.
Qxb6 is helping Black, because it opens the "a" file, the same is valid for
Qxb3 as well. Both sides are trying to force queen exchange, White, by means
of Nd2-c4 and Black by means of Be6. In the following example, GM Jenni
chooses the setup with "d7-d5," which in my opinion is less flexible than
"d7-d6".} d5 8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. Be2 c4 10. Qa3 {In the systems with "e7-e6," this
queen's retreat is not possible. Now the queen is perfectly placed on "a3,"
and the bishop on "g7 is passive. White is ready to continue with the typical
"b2-b3"} Qa5 11. Qxa5 Nxa5 12. b3 b5 (12... cxb3 {as always this move is a
concession and White is simply better after;} 13. axb3 Nc6 14. b4 $16) 13. b4 (
13. O-O a6 14. Ne5 $16) 13... Nc6 (13... Nb7 $1 {The best defence} 14. a4 bxa4
15. Rxa4 a5 16. Ne5 {My engine is trying to convince me that this is equality,
but I am not sure about it. Still, it seems to me that White's position
remains preferable.}) 14. a4 bxa4 15. Rxa4 a5 16. Ne5 ({There is nothing wrong
with} 16. b5 Nd8 17. O-O $16) 16... Bb7 17. bxa5 ({I am not sure why White
didn't take a pawn with:} 17. Nxc6 Bxc6 18. Rxa5) 17... Rxa5 18. Rxa5 Nxa5 19.
O-O Ra8 20. Rb1 {Black is without any counterplay and his pieces are strangely
placed. Sooner or later, White's pieces should be able to penetrate in Black's
camp.} Ne8 21. Bf3 Nd6 22. Nd7 {Suddenly, Black has problems defending his
"d5" pawn.} Bc6 (22... Rd8 {was the only move that keeps Black in the game but
after} 23. Nc5 Bc6 24. Bxd6 $1 Rxd6 (24... exd6 $2 25. Na6 $18 {[%cal Ra6b4]})
25. Ra1 Nb3 (25... Nb7 $2 26. Nxc4 $1 $18) 26. Ndxb3 cxb3 27. Nxb3 {White
should be able to convert his extra point.}) 23. Nb6 Rb8 24. Nxd5 Rxb1+ 25.
Nxb1 Kf8 26. Bxd6 exd6 27. Nb6 Bxf3 28. gxf3 Ke7 29. Nd2 {Black loses a second
pawn. Another very well-played game by Gata Kamsky} 1-0

