{[%evp 0,67,19,31,14,30,45,43,45,34,24,36,21,29,16,7,-1,-10,9,14,15,15,23,11,
10,22,23,28,24,14,32,19,40,40,32,45,43,58,82,59,64,64,64,71,77,-10,64,76,3,0,0,
0,0,0,15,0,82,90,108,98,94,121,125,133,141,141,141,146,295,283] In this and
the next example we will see positions when Black exchanged the queens on "b3".
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. h3 c5 6. c3 cxd4 (6... Qb6 {
Sometimes Black prefers to play this move immediately, without including cxd4.}
) (6... d6 {Allows White to enter the endgame, which we discussed in the
previous games} 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Qxd8) (6... b6 {Is another approach which
deserves serious attention}) 7. exd4 d6 8. Be2 Qb6 9. Qb3 Qxb3 (9... Nc6 10.
Qxb6 axb6 {This structure is usually unpleasant for Black, but Black can
probably keep the balance with an accurate play.} 11. Na3 Nd5 $11 {[%cal Rc8d7,
Rf8c8]}) 10. axb3 Nc6 11. O-O e5 (11... Re8 {Is too slow} 12. Na3 e5 13. dxe5
dxe5 14. Bh2 e4 15. Nd2 $14) 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Bh2 dxe5 14. Rd1 {Understanding
this position is crucial. White is better here, despite his better pawn
structure. Our double pawns on the "b" file control important squares. White
wants to play Nd2 followed by Nc4 and b4-b5.} (14. b4 $14) 14... Nb6 (14... Be6
15. Ng5 Nc7 16. Nxe6 Nxe6 17. b4 $14) (14... Nf4 15. Bxf4 exf4 16. Nbd2 $14 {
with b4-b5}) (14... Rd8 15. Na3 $14 {It is better to keep the "d2" square
available for the other knight}) (14... Nde7 15. b4 $36) 15. Nbd2 (15. Na3 a6
16. b4) 15... Be6 16. b4 {with b5 xe5} f6 {Black manages to lock our bishop on
"h2" but "c5" and "d6" squares are very weak and White takes advantage of this.
} 17. Ne4 $14 Bd5 $6 (17... Rf7 18. b5 Nd8 19. Rd6 $18) (17... Bc4 18. Bxc4+
Nxc4 19. b3 Nb6 20. b5 $14) (17... Bb3 $1 {Black should try to seek for some
counterplay with} 18. Rd2 a5 19. Nc5 $14 {White is still better}) 18. Nd6 (18.
Nc5 {is fine too} Ne7 19. b3 a6 20. c4 $14 Bc6 21. Ne6 Rfc8 22. g4 {[%cal
Rg4g5,Rd1d6] With a complete domination over the board}) 18... Ne7 19. c4 Rfd8
(19... Rad8 $1 20. c5 Nbc8 21. Rxd5 Nxd5 22. Nxc8 Rxc8 23. Bc4 Rfd8 24. Rd1 $16
) 20. c5 $14 {Kamsky-P Wolff, Philadelphia 1991} a6 21. Ra5 $2 {is just a
waste of time} (21. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Rd2e4,Rf2f4]}) 21... Kf8 22. g4 g5 $4 {
terrible positional move. Black is defending against g4-g5, but this wast
necessary} ({With the rook on "a5" White's pieces are not so well coordinated
and Black should try to use this by means of} 22... Bc4 $1 23. Kf1 Bxe2+ 24.
Kxe2 Nbd5 {White's knight on "d6" is still very strong, by the position
remains playable, and Black has good chances to survive.} 25. b5 axb5 26. Rxb5
b6 {with a wild complication in which it seems that Black is doing just well})
23. b5 $4 {another mistake} (23. Nd4 $1 {is the key idea which leads to
winning position for White} exd4 24. cxb6 $18 {The bishop on "h2" is active
now and Black can't defend the "b7" pawn comfortably.}) 23... axb5 24. Rxb5 Na4
25. Rxd5 $5 {An interesting attempt that poses some practical problems.} Nxd5
26. Nxb7 Rdb8 27. c6 Ne7 $4 (27... Nc7 $1 $11 {is the logical improvement and
seems to hold}) 28. Nd4 $1 $18 {Now is over. The tactics seem to work just
great for White} exd4 29. Bxb8 Rxb8 30. c7 Rc8 31. Nd6 Rxc7 32. Rb8+ Nc8 33.
Nxc8 f5 34. Nb6+ {Interesting fighting game with many mistakes from both sides.
It is interesting to see how sharp those middlegames without queens can be.}
1-0

