1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. h3 d5 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e3 cxd4 8. exd4
Nc6 9. Be2 Qb6 10. Qb3 Qxb3 11. axb3 {Again, we see the endgame after Qxb3.
This position is hard for Black. We can say that White has a free advantage on
the queenside with the obvious plan b4-b5 followed by Nd2-b3-c5, supporting
with the bishops on "f3" and "f4". The other plan is just to double the rooks
on the "a" file} Bf5 12. b4 a6 13. Nb3 Nd7 14. O-O Bc2 15. Nbd2 {Kamsky almost
always chooses the simplest move, which is an excellent strategy, especially
for blitz games.} (15. Na5 $1 {was stronger} Nxa5 16. Rxa5 e6 17. b5 $16) (15.
Nc5 Nxc5 16. bxc5 $16) 15... f6 16. Ne1 Bf5 17. Bf3 Be6 18. Nc2 Bf7 19. Nb3 e5
20. Bh2 e4 $6 (20... f5 {[%cal Rf5f4] was stronger} 21. Rfd1 f4 22. dxe5 Ndxe5
23. Bxd5 Bxd5 24. Rxd5 Nc4 {with some compensation for the pawn}) 21. Be2 f5
22. Nc5 $1 {Now Kamsky changes the structure in his favour} Nxc5 23. bxc5 Be6
24. Bd6 Rfc8 25. f4 $1 {Really instructive play by Kamsky. He blocked the
kingside, securing a nice "e3" square for his knight and then proceed with his
plan on the queenside.} Bf8 26. Bxf8 Kxf8 27. Ne3 Ne7 28. Ra3 Ke8 29. g3 Kd7
30. Rfa1 h6 31. h4 g5 32. h5 {Kamsky prefers to keep the kingside closed} g4
33. Kf2 Bf7 34. b4 Rab8 35. Rh1 (35. b5 $1 {was much faster} axb5 36. Bxb5+ Nc6
(36... Ke6 37. Ra6+ $3 $18) (36... Kc7 37. Ra7 {[%cal Rc3c4]}) 37. Nxf5 $18)
35... Ke6 36. c4 Kf6 37. cxd5 Nxd5 $6 (37... Bxd5 $1 {was better}) 38. Nxd5+
Bxd5 39. Ke3 Rd8 40. Rb1 Bc6 41. Ra5 Be8 42. Bc4 Bxh5 43. b5 axb5 44. Raxb5 Be8
45. Rb6+ Kg7 46. Rxb7+ Rxb7 47. Rxb7+ $18 {the rest is not important} Kf6 48.
Rb6+ Kg7 49. Be6 Kf6 50. Bc8+ Kg7 51. Bxf5 Ra8 52. Rb3 Bf7 53. Rc3 Bd5 54. c6
Kf6 55. Bxg4 h5 56. Bh3 Rg8 57. Kf2 Be6 58. Bxe6 Kxe6 59. c7 Rc8 60. Ke3 Kd7
61. Kxe4 Re8+ 62. Kf5 Kc8 63. Kg5 1-0

