{[%evp 0,103,31,30,30,30,54,36,32,4,33,30,46,25,52,51,37,37,96,38,48,10,75,25,
54,43,70,86,102,87,100,96,113,61,56,52,60,44,53,36,80,92,96,124,135,93,119,140,
120,91,100,100,152,117,146,134,118,110,105,110,124,93,92,90,99,102,107,95,95,
88,81,60,82,82,112,112,119,103,123,114,159,144,157,147,150,140,182,165,184,184,
184,183,199,183,214,203,203,127,132,127,114,114,155,155,155,172]} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. h3 c5 6. e3 Qb6 {A fairly critical test of
White's move order.} 7. Qb3 d6 8. Nbd2 Be6 9. Bc4 $1 ({With the knight still
on "b8" Black can comfortably meet} 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. Nc4 {with} (10. a3 Bd5 (
10... cxd4 11. exd4) 11. Bd3 Bc6 12. e4 Rd8 13. Be3 b5 14. Ke2 Na6 15. b4 $4 c4
(15... d5 16. e5 Ne4 17. Rhc1 c4 18. Bb1 f6) 16. Bc2 Nc7 {0-1 (37) Bykov,E 
(2050)-Panarin,M (2555) Sochi 2014}) 10... Nbd7 {.}) (9. c4 Na6 10. a3 Qxb3 11.
Nxb3 cxd4 12. Nbxd4 Bd7 13. Bh2 Nc5 14. Nd2 a5 {0-1 (54) Bierenbroodspot,P 
(2310)-De Rover,Y}) 9... Bxc4 (9... d5 10. Be2 c4 11. Qc2 Bf5 12. Qc1 Qa5 13.
b3 $14 {1-0 (27) Jumabayev,R (2654)-Sorkin,I (2383) chess.com INT 2020 and if}
b5 $2 14. a4 $1 $16) 10. Nxc4 Qa6 {and after} (10... Qc6 $5 {is a very nice
idea. Black wants to continue with b7-b5.} 11. O-O ({White can't win the pawn
after} 11. Na5 Qb6 12. Nxb7 $2 Nbd7 {and the "b7" knight is trapped}) 11...
Nbd7 (11... b5 $5 {looks like a logical continuation too} 12. Ncd2 Nbd7 13. a4
a6 {The position is objectively equal, but I prefer Black here.}) 12. a4 $13 {
White won a nice game in G. Kamsky - I. Chirila - 2015 1-0}) (10... Qc7 11. O-O
Nbd7 12. a4 b6 13. Rfd1 Rab8 $11 {0-1 (35) Kachko,A (2328)-Chigaev,M (2588)
chess.com INT 2020}) 11. O-O Nc6 ({not} 11... b5 $6 12. Na3 $1 {and White is
winning a pawn}) (11... Nbd7 $5 {"d7" seems to be a better square for the
queenside knight} 12. a4 Rac8 $11) 12. a4 {"b7-b5" is no longer possible} Nd5
13. dxc5 $1 (13. Qb5 $2 {is losing a pawn} Nxf4 14. exf4 cxd4) (13. Bh2 cxd4 $1
{and White's bishop on "h2" is not taking part into the game}) 13... Nxf4 (
13... dxc5 14. Qb5 $16) 14. exf4 dxc5 15. Qb5 $1 $16 {White forces a
favourable endgame} Rac8 (15... Qxb5 $4 {is losing by force after} 16. axb5 Nd8
17. Nb6 $18) 16. Qxa6 bxa6 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 18. Kf1 {the game is practically over.
Our minor pieces are more active and Black's structure on the queenside is
awful. I will leave the rest of the game without comments, but Tomashevksy won
without any problems.} Kf8 19. Nfd2 e6 20. Ne4 Rd5 21. Ne3 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Nb8
23. Nc4 Ke7 24. Ke2 Nd7 25. Rd6 Bh6 26. g3 f5 27. Ned2 Nb8 28. Nf3 Rc6 29. Rd1
Bg7 30. h4 Rc7 31. h5 gxh5 32. Rh1 Nd7 33. Rxh5 h6 34. Rh1 Nb6 35. Nfd2 Nxa4
36. Ra1 Nb6 37. Rxa6 Nd5 38. Nf3 Bf6 39. Kd3 h5 40. Ng5 Bxg5 41. fxg5 Rd7 42.
Ke2 Rb7 43. f4 h4 44. gxh4 Nxf4+ 45. Kf3 Nh5 46. Ne5 Rxb2 47. Rxa7+ Kf8 48.
Ng6+ Kg8 49. Nf4 Nxf4 50. Kxf4 Re2 51. g6 Rg2 52. h5 {1-0 (52) Tomashevsky,E 
(2714)-Gelfand,B (2759) Sochi 2014} *

