1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be2 c5 7. c3 Qb6 8. Qb3
Be6 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. a3 {This time we will check the position where White
exchanges queens on the "b6" square. This is an important theoretical position,
and we can conclude that Black is doing well in such a structure.} Nc6 {
At that time the plan the players didn't know the plan with Bd5} (10... Bd5 $1
{The well-known idea is Bd5 (or Bd7) followed by Bc6 and Nbd7. Then Black can
expand on the queenside by means of b5-b4}) 11. Nbd2 Na5 {this is the main
idea in the 10...Nc6 line. Black's main idea is to stop Nc4, but there is
another hidden idea which is to slow down "e3-e4"} (11... Rfe8 {was played
later by Sokolov, but this seems to be too slow. The idea is to push "e7-e5",
but this is not the best plan}) 12. O-O (12. e4 Nb3 $1 {This is the key idea}
13. Nxb3 (13. Rd1 cxd4 14. cxd4 Rfc8 $5 $11) 13... Bxb3 14. Bd3 c4 (14... b5 $5
) 15. Bb1 b5 {and Black is doing fine}) 12... Rfc8 13. Rfc1 Bb3 (13... Nb3 {
was more natural} 14. Nxb3 Bxb3 $11 {with an equal position}) 14. Bd3 Nd7 (
14... Ba4 {[%cal Rb6b5] with the idea "b6-b5" was better.}) 15. Bb5 Nf8 16. a4
$14 {White is better here. The knight on "f8" is misplaced and White is in
control in the centre and on the queenside. Later on, White could try to
expand by means of "e3-e4"} Ne6 17. Bg3 Nc7 18. c4 cxd4 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. exd4
Ne6 21. Bd7 $4 {strange mistake for a player on that level} (21. d5 Nd4 22. Kh2
$16 {White has a big advantage. The concentration of Black's pieces on the
queenside doesn't promise him anything.}) 21... Nxd4 $1 $17 {just wins a pawn
and the game} 22. Bxc8 Ne2+ 23. Kh1 Nxc1 24. Bg4 Nd3 25. Ra3 Nxb2 26. Nxb3
Nbxc4 27. Nxa5 Nxa3 28. Nxb7 Rxa4 29. Bd7 Rc4 {The "b7" knight is trapped} 0-1

