{[%evp 0,93,13,29,29,29,27,27,59,16,14,14,16,24,40,28,11,24,73,64,64,64,64,64,
88,76,101,79,93,93,81,84,88,85,81,52,70,79,81,84,94,100,100,106,181,155,170,
185,196,194,211,195,217,186,202,183,235,233,229,235,246,235,230,254,267,259,
220,239,231,227,309,308,278,219,225,221,221,221,221,221,221,197,181,176,183,
157,273,210,210,202,313,319,403,385,441,448]} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4.
c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Qb6 6. Qb3 g6 7. Qxb6 {From a different opening we reach similar
position to London system with the exchanged queens on "b6". This is an
endgame which you must avoid.} axb6 8. Bc7 {Black's pawns are immobilazed and
the "b6" one is very weak. Black must defend it with Nd7, which tied all other
pieces. White has a very simple plan: just play Bb5 followed by Nf3, 0-0 and
opening the queenside in an appropriate momment.} Nd7 9. Bb5 Bg7 10. Ngf3 O-O
11. O-O e6 12. a4 Bf6 13. Rfc1 Bd8 14. Bd6 Be7 15. Bc7 Bd8 16. Bg3 $1 {Of
course White should keep more pieces on the board} Bf6 17. Nb3 (17. h3 {
I would prefer some neutral move like this, because it is not so clear how
Black can continue. Later on, White can think to open the position with e4 or
c4 breaks.} Re8 18. e4 $1 $16) 17... c4 ({The knight goes far from the centre
and Black should use that by means of} 17... e5 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. c4 d4 20.
exd4 $16 {White is still much better, but at least Black can breath}) 18. Nbd2
Re8 19. b3 cxb3 20. Nxb3 Nf8 21. c4 dxc4 22. Nbd2 $18 {The game is practically
over. I will leave the rest of it without comments.} c3 23. Nc4 Nd7 24. Rxc3
Be7 25. Rac1 f6 26. e4 Bb4 27. Rd3 Ba5 28. Rdd1 Na7 29. Nd6 Rd8 30. Bc4 Nf8 31.
e5 Bb4 32. Nxc8 Raxc8 33. exf6 Ba3 34. Rc2 b5 35. axb5 Nxb5 36. Rb1 Nd6 37.
Bxd6 Bxd6 38. Rxb7 Rc7 39. Rxc7 Bxc7 40. g4 h6 41. h4 Bf4 42. Re2 Rd6 43. g5
hxg5 44. hxg5 Nh7 45. Bxe6+ Kf8 46. Nh4 Bxg5 47. Nxg6+ 1-0

