{[%evp 0,86,30,29,27,27,47,47,25,3,68,31,28,28,28,16,33,7,18,0,-8,-5,16,-7,-5,
-9,-5,-5,-1,5,38,-5,-5,-33,22,22,20,29,36,48,47,47,47,47,63,-4,48,48,45,45,30,
28,39,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,28,0,0,0,0,-76,-76,-76,-54,-51,-51,-171,-171,-171,-212,
-171,-212,-171,-200,-192,-200,-200,-203,-203,-139,-225,-469]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
g6 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. c3 c5 5. e3 Qb6 6. Qb3 O-O 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Yb6b3]} d6 8. Qxb6
axb6 9. Nc4 {Again we have the same structure with exchanged queens on "b6".
The only difference is that the bishop is on "g5". He is going to "f4" very
soon and we will transpose to the London system. White puts pressure on "b6",
but with the knight still on "b8", it is effortless to defend the pawn.} Nbd7 (
9... b5 $5 {is possible but risky} 10. Nb6 Ra5 11. b4 cxb4 12. cxb4 Ra3 13.
Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Bxb5 Nc6 $44) 10. Be2 d5 (10... b5 $5 {was possible again} 11.
Na3 b4 12. cxb4 cxd4 $3 {very nice pawn sacrifice} (12... cxb4 13. Nc2 $16 {
[%csl Rb4]}) 13. Nxd4 Nd5 {and Black has enough compensation for the
sacrificing pawn.}) 11. Nce5 h6 12. Bf4 c4 {[%csl Ge4] Interesting decision by
Kasparov White can't organize e3-e4 quickly so Black can release the tension
in the center and start his play on the queenside} (12... g5 $5 {Leela prefers
to keep the tension and to play} 13. Bg3 (13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. Bc7 b5 {Black is
trying to play on the queenside without "c5-c4"} 15. dxc5 $2 {is just a mistake
} Ne4 $17) 13... Ne4 {I like Black's position here}) 13. h4 (13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14.
Ne5 $14 {was the simplest way to continue}) 13... b5 (13... h5 $5 $10 {It
makes a lot of sense to start with this move. Not allowing White to expand on
the kingside}) 14. g4 Nb6 15. g5 hxg5 16. hxg5 Ne4 17. Nd2 {[%csl Ge4]} (17. a3
$2 {Black has an instructive idea in this structure} Na4 $1 18. Ra2 Nxb2 19.
Rxb2 Rxa3 $17) 17... Bf5 (17... Na4 {is also possible} 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. O-O-O
$36 {[%cal Rh1h8,Ga2a3]} Nxc3 $1 20. bxc3 Rxa2 {It seems that Black has more
than enough for the piece.}) (17... Nxd2 $2 18. Kxd2 Na4 $6 19. b3 Nb6 20. bxc4
$16) 18. Bg4 Na4 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Bxf5 gxf5 21. Rb1 b4 $1 {Black is
sacrificing a pawn, but keeps his dinamic chances and opens the queenside.} 22.
cxb4 Nb6 $5 (22... c3 $1 23. bxc3 (23. b3 $5 Nb2 24. a4 Nd3+ $1 {[%csl Rc3]}
25. Ke2 Nxf4+ 26. exf4 Rfd8 $11) 23... Nxc3 24. Rb2 Nd5 {[%cal Rd5f4,Rf8c8,
Ra8a3]}) 23. a3 Rfc8 24. g6 Bxe5 25. gxf7+ Kxf7 26. Bxe5 Nd5 {[%csl Gd5,Re5]
This is the endgame that I wanted to show. Black's knight is definitely
stronger than White's bishop and compensates the missing pawn. The position is
objectively equal but practically easier to play for Black. You should always
try to avoid such positions with White.} 27. Kd2 c3+ 28. Kc2 (28. bxc3 Rxa3 $17
) 28... cxb2+ 29. Kxb2 Rc3 30. Ra1 (30. Rbc1 $5 Rcxa3 31. Rh7+ Ke6 32. Rh6+ Kd7
33. Rc5 {and the engine insist that this is just equal}) (30. Rh5 Raxa3 $19)
30... b5 {[%cal Yc3d3,Yd5b6,Yb6c4]} 31. Rhc1 Rd3 32. Rc5 Nb6 $1 33. Rxb5 (33.
Kc2 $1 {this move saves the game} Nc4 34. a4 Na3+) 33... Nc4+ 34. Kc1 (34. Kc2
Nxa3+ 35. Kc1 Rg8 36. Rc5 Rg1+ 37. Kb2 Rd2+ $19) 34... Rg8 35. Bg3 f4 $3 $19
36. Rf5+ (36. Bxf4 Rc3+ $1 37. Kd1 (37. Kb1 Rg1+ 38. Ka2 Rxa3#) 37... Rg1+ 38.
Ke2 Rc2#) (36. exf4 Rc3+ $1 (36... e3 37. Kc2 $1 (37. Ra2 Rd2 38. Rxd2 exd2+
39. Kd1 Rh8 $19) 37... Rxa3 38. Rf5+ $132) 37. Kd1 $8 (37. Kb1 Rh8 $40) 37...
Rh8) 36... Kg6 37. Rxf4 Rc8 {[%cal Rc4a3]} 38. Rg4+ (38. Kb1 Nd2+ 39. Kb2 Rb3+
40. Ka2 Rc2#) 38... Kh5 39. Rh4+ Kg6 40. Rg4+ Kh5 41. Rh4+ Kg5 $1 42. f4+ Kg6
43. f5+ Kg5 ({The checks are over and White's king is in the mating net} 43...
Kg5 44. Rh2 Nd2+ 45. Kd1 Nb1+ $1 46. Ke2 Rc2+ 47. Kf1 Rd1+ 48. Be1 Rxh2 $19)
0-1

