{[%evp 0,87,29,32,24,32,47,47,40,40,50,37,44,8,8,12,18,2,-11,5,29,29,34,38,51,
44,28,11,9,8,8,8,0,0,-13,-13,-21,-8,5,-21,-17,-23,-30,-68,-46,-124,-98,-157,
-163,-163,-137,-141,-149,-174,-184,-181,-163,-150,-57,-57,54,58,54,-96,33,42,
48,8,144,84,127,122,152,124,118,121,124,130,115,119,195,158,252,262,276,276,
285,296,277,268]} 1. d4 {The reason why I decided to present this game is to
answer the crucial question "Which are the best lines for Black that White
should avoid?" In general, I believe that: 1) the system with early d6-c5-cxd4
and 2) d6-c5-Qb6 (without Nbd7 played) are the best choices for Black after
which White cannot get a better position out of the opening.} Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3.
Bf4 Bg7 (3... d6 {is a tricky move order because most people automatically
continue 4.e3. However, this allows Black to easily play 4...c5. Instead, the
right way for White, in my opinion, is} 4. c3 ({After the inaccurate} 4. e3 {
Black quickly plays} c5 {and after} 5. c3 ({The point is that} 5. dxc5 {
is met by} Qa5+ $11) {Black gets a comfortable position with either} 5... Qb6 (
{or} 5... cxd4)) {Now} 4... c5 $6 {simply does not work in the view of} 5. dxc5
dxc5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Na3 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Ga3b5] and Black has a terrible
endgame.}) 4. e3 d6 {Move orders are important. In this position,} 5. h3 {
despite being a standard move in the London system, is a well-known inaccuracy!
} ({Once again} 5. c3 $1 {is the best way to preempt c5, as in the note to
move 4.}) 5... c5 6. c3 ({This time} 6. dxc5 {is best answered with} Ne4 $1 {
[%cal Re4c5,Re7e5]} 7. Bd3 Nxc5 {[%csl Rd6,Re7,Rf7][%cal Re7e5] when Black has
good opportunities in the center.}) 6... Qb6 {This is a variation that I would
recommend to players with a good endgame technique.} (6... cxd4 {is a good
alternative, as we will see in other examples. It provides more complex
positions compared to 6...Qb6.}) 7. Qb3 Be6 {This move is possible only when
Black plays ...c5 quickly, without the previous Nbd7. This is an important
nuance that allows Black to get a comfortable endgame.} 8. Qxb6 (8. Qa3 {
is not a completely correct move, which I have sometimes played as a
semi-bluff. However, Black needs to know the exact moves to take advantage of
it:} cxd4 $1 {This is the strongest move, though surprisingly a few people
have played it. Otherwise, White gets a nice position with Nbd2-c4, etc.} 9.
exd4 ({After} 9. cxd4 Nd5 $1 10. Bg3 Qb4+ {Black forces a better endgame.} 11.
Nbd2 (11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. Kd2 Bxa2) 11... Qxa3 12. bxa3 Nb6 $17 {[%csl Ra2,Ra3]})
9... O-O 10. Be2 {and now the key idea for Black is} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Ra3]
preparing to emphasize a poor position of the white queen on a3 with the pawn
advances b5 and a5.} 11. O-O b5 12. Nbd2 a5 $17 {[%csl Ra3]}) 8... axb6 9. a3 {
In this pawn structure, Black's main idea is to transfer their light-squared
bishop to the diagonal a8-h1. Thus, Black plays} Bd7 $1 (9... Bd5 $5 {is not
worse, preparing to put the bishop on c6 anyway.}) 10. Nbd2 Bc6 11. Bd3 O-O 12.
O-O Nbd7 {[%cal Rb6b5,Rc5c4,Rd7b6] Black has a comfortable position. Thanks to
the bishop on c6, he can prepare ...b6-b5, c4, etc. On the other hand, one of
the main positional problems for White is the passive bishop on f4. The game
continued:} 13. e4 (13. Rfe1 e5 $5 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Bxe5 (15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16.
Bxe5 Rfd8 $19) 15... Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Rfd8 $44) (13. Bh2 e5 $1) 13... cxd4 14.
cxd4 (14. Nxd4 Nc5 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Bc2 b5 17. Be3 Na4 $15) 14... e5 $1 {
An important move for Black and typically the best way to meet White's e4. The
tactical point is that White cannot capture the pawn because of his hanging
pieces on the d-file.} 15. Bh2 (15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Be3 (16. Nxe5 $4 Nxe5 17.
Bxe5 Rfd8 $19 {[%csl Rd2,Rd3]}) 16... Nc5 {[%cal Rc5d3,Rc5e4]} 17. Bxc5 bxc5
18. Nxe5 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Bxe4 20. Nxe4 Bxe5 21. Nxc5 Bxb2 22. Ra2 Bxa3 23. Nxb7
Be7 $11) 15... exd4 16. Bxd6 Rfe8 17. e5 Nd5 18. Rfe1 Nf4 19. Bf1 Ne6 20. b4 b5
$1 {Black position is already slightly more pleasant, but Le Quang made things
worse by playing} 21. g3 $2 (21. Nb3 Bxf3 22. gxf3 Ng5 23. Kg2 Nxe5) 21... Nb6
22. Nh2 Nc8 ({Volokitin could have gotten a more or less winning position if
he had played} 22... Red8 $1 23. Bd3 Ra4 {[%cal Rd8a8,Rb6c4] instead.}) 23. Nb3
Nxd6 24. exd6 Rad8 25. Na5 Rxd6 26. Bg2 d3 27. Rad1 d2 28. Re3 Red8 (28... Bxg2
29. Kxg2 Bh6) 29. Bxc6 bxc6 30. Nb7 Bh6 31. Re4 Nd4 32. Nxd6 Rxd6 33. f4 Bf8
34. Nf1 c5 35. bxc5 Rd5 36. Ne3 Rd8 37. Kg2 Nb3 38. c6 Rc8 39. Rb1 Nc1 40. Rd4
Rxc6 41. Rxd2 Bxa3 42. Rxb5 Rc3 43. Nd5 Rc6 44. Ra5 1-0

