{[%evp 0,59,32,24,32,38,47,40,40,38,40,7,18,17,11,12,4,7,36,8,8,6,16,-2,24,20,
41,56,65,57,59,51,50,50,42,42,49,44,84,49,140,86,63,60,143,106,106,106,164,163,
278,315,764,835,835,927,29993,29994,29995,29994,29995,29996]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. c3 {Once again, if you want to avoid the systems
with early c5, this is the correct move order for White.} Nh5 {A fairly rare,
but interesting move.} (5... c5 6. dxc5 $1) 6. Bg5 {This is a classical way to
meet Nh5,} ({however, White can be even more creative with} 6. h4 $5 {This is
an idea of Eugenio Torre (from a similar position). It is an interesting
back-up plan for White. He could get an attack in some lines, although the
black position is absolutely fine if Black plays the best moves. However, not
many people may find them over the board. White threatens to retreat the
bishop to h2 now, so it makes the most sense to take it} Nxf4 7. exf4 {[#]
What is Black's most likely response in this position?} h5 {is quite a natural
way to stop White's attack, but at the same time, a bad choice.} (7... O-O {
is probably the best reply. White's attack is not as dangerous as it might
seem due to his rather poor development. On the other hand, Black is in time
to open up the centre with e7-e5 before White manages to mobilize his forces
for the attack.} 8. Nbd2 Nd7 9. h5 e5 $132) (7... Nd7 {is also playable,
trying to carry out ...e5 immediately.} 8. Nbd2 e5 9. fxe5 dxe5 10. dxe5 Nxe5
11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Qf3 {[%cal Re1c1,Rf1c4,Rh4h5] White has a slight initiative,
though Black should probably be fine after} Qf6) (7... Bg4 {stops h5, but the
bishop does not belong to g4.} 8. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd1b3]}) {White can now play} 8.
Ng5 $36 {creating some pressure on the kingside. For example} O-O (8... f6 9.
Nf3 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Rf1d3,Rd3g6]}) 9. Bd3 Nd7 (9... Nc6 10. d5) 10. f5 $40)
6... h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 ({In my view the best way to react to this move is} 8.
Nfd2 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Rd1h5] which enables us to preserve the dark-squared
bishop from an exchange.} Nf6 9. Bg3 $14 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Rh2h4,Gc3c4,Gb1c3,
Rb1a3] If Black castles kingside, we can undermine his pawn shield with h2-h4.
Nb1 can be developed to c3 or a3.}) 8... b6 {Black is better off postponing
the decision whether to take on g3 or not until White shows his cards. In some
cases, he may even try to trap the bishop with ...f7-f5-f4, etc.} ({Another
option is} 8... O-O 9. Bd3 f5 10. Nbd2 e6 11. Qe2 Nd7 12. Bc2 b6 13. h3 Nxg3
14. fxg3 Bb7 15. g4 {[%cal Re2d3,Rd3h7,Re1c1]}) 9. Nbd2 Bb7 10. Qa4+ $5 {
A tricky move played with the idea to either exchange the light-squared
bishops, leaving black only with the worse g7-bishop, or to provoke c6 which
blocks the light-squared one.} c6 (10... Nd7 11. Ba6 $14) ({If} 10... Qd7 {
then White can still provoke weakening in black structure with} 11. Bb5 c6 12.
Bd3) 11. Be2 b5 $6 {This is a committal move from a positional point of view.
The bishop on b7 is a rather bad piece now and b5-pawn may become vulnerable.}
12. Qb3 Nxg3 (12... Nd7 {meets a nice tactical refutation} 13. Ne5 $1 {[%csl
Rf7,Rh5][%cal Rc4f7,Re2h5]}) 13. hxg3 Qb6 {[#] White has a couple of
'classical' moves in this position. Firstly, there is} 14. a4 {attacking
Black's queenside structure,} ({and secondly,} 14. g4 $14 {[%csl Rg5,Rh6][%cal
Rd2e4,Re4g3,Rg3f5] fixing the pawn structure on the kingside. Later White can
transfer a knight to g3 with a positional advantage thanks to the weak h6-pawn.
}) 14... a6 15. c4 {Now the b5-pawn is under serious fire and Black needs to
give it up.} Nd7 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8+ Bxa8 18. cxb5 c5 $2 {A losing mistake.
} ({Black would have kept some compensation for the pawn by playing the
'automatic' move} 18... O-O 19. bxc6 Qxc6 20. O-O Rb8) 19. Bc4 cxd4 {Another
strange decision.} (19... O-O {simply had to be played.}) 20. Bxf7+ Kd8 21. Nc4
Qc5 22. Nxd4 Bxd4 23. exd4 Qxd4 24. O-O {Black king is too exposed and the end
is near.} Rf8 25. Qa3 Bd5 26. Qa5+ Kc8 27. Rc1 Kb7 28. Nxd6+ exd6 29. Qc7+ Ka8
30. Ra1+ 1-0

