{[%evp 0,113,25,28,27,27,73,44,44,44,98,48,82,39,33,33,23,22,28,-12,-12,-12,4,
10,29,-10,39,2,40,-7,42,35,37,34,34,34,67,34,68,68,68,68,68,68,194,107,168,173,
194,194,194,194,194,194,193,213,220,191,184,182,222,235,257,245,248,260,265,
265,461,315,298,277,275,276,351,261,260,274,297,263,266,261,271,274,278,256,
270,260,273,270,276,276,287,300,337,331,386,327,346,349,386,367,436,394,415,
429,641,841,833,885,1212,1315,1461,1408,1408,1669]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4
d6 4. e3 {As discussed in game 1, this is slightly inaccurate.} (4. c3 c5 5.
dxc5) 4... c5 5. c3 Nbd7 {A strange decision considering the fact that both ...
cxd4 and ...Qb6 are preferable choices for Black, as I explained in game 1.} 6.
h3 Bg7 7. Bd3 {Le Quang anticipates Nakamura's plan to develop with ...b6, so
he puts his bishop on d3 instead of e2. This is the best square for the bishop
as it supports the e3-e4 break.} O-O 8. O-O b6 {A common developing scheme for
Black.} 9. Bh2 {This is a good prophylactic move because it helps White avoid
complications with ...e7-e5 break, as we have seen in game 1.} ({For example:} 
9. Nbd2 Bb7 10. a4 cxd4 11. exd4 e5 $1 12. dxe5 $4 dxe5 13. Bxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5
Nh5 15. Ndf3 Bxe5 $1 16. Nxe5 Nf4 $19) 9... Bb7 10. Nbd2 Qc7 11. e4 {[%cal
Ge4e5] This is a natural follow-up,} ({but} 11. a4 {seems like a more accurate
approach. The idea behind a4 is to secure the c4-square and also to provoke ...
a6 as a permanent weakness in Black's camp. Later, White plays Qe2 -
supporting e4 and attacking the a6 pawn at the same time.} a6 12. Qe2 {[%cal
Ge3e4] I have played this position myself several times and I believe that it
is slightly better for White.}) 11... e5 12. Re1 Rfe8 13. a4 a6 14. dxe5 {
White should play this move sooner or later. Black has a typical choice now
between} dxe5 ({and} 14... Nxe5 {In my view, Black should generally prefer
this recapture as it allows him to exchange a pair of knights and free up his
play a bit. It also helps him control the critical squares on the d-file (like
d6) better with Rfd8 later. For example:} 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Qe2 {[%csl Ra4,Ra6]
} Nh5 17. Bc4 Nf4 18. Qf1 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Rc4a6,Rf1c4] In my view, White
still keeps slightly better chances thanks to the pressure on a6.} Red8 19. Nf3
h6 20. Bxf4 exf4 21. Qe2 {White goes for the light-squares strategy.} Re8 22.
Qc2 Rad8 23. Re2 g5 24. Rae1 {[%cal Re4e5] White can already consider pushing
the pawn forward. White generally has a better knight than black dark-squared
bishop.}) 15. Qb3 Nh5 {This is a standard plan for Black.} 16. Rad1 Nf4 17. Bc4
{White has a nice positional pressure in a symmetrical position. Black has
some problems due to the weak d6 and d5 squares, as well as the pawn on f7. I
also don't trust black bishops here. They need more space and open diagonals
to become effective.} Re7 18. Nf1 $1 {The beginning of the plan to take
control over the d5-outpost.} Nf6 (18... h6 {[#] stops Ng5, but} 19. Ne3 $1 {
is positionally strong because the pawn on e4 is defended by tactical means.}
b5 {may have to be played to deflect white pieces from a2-g8 diagonal.} (19...
Bxe4 20. Bxf4 exf4 (20... Bxf3 21. gxf3 exf4 22. Bxf7+ $1 {A powerful
intermezzo.} Rxf7 23. Nd5 {[%cal Rd5e7]} Qa7 24. Ne7+ Kf8 25. Nxg6+ Kg8 26. Re7
$18) 21. Nd5 $18) 20. axb5 axb5 21. Qxb5 Bxe4 {Still, White can force a
superior endgame with} 22. Bxf4 Bxf3 23. Nd5 Bxd5 24. Bxd5 Rb8 25. Qc6 Qxc6 26.
Bxc6 Nb6 27. Bb5 Nd5 28. Rxd5 Rxb5 29. b4 $16) 19. Ng5 $1 {Powerful play by Le
Quang. Nakamura already had some serious problems to solve.} b5 (19... h6 {
[#] loses to} 20. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 21. Bxf4 exf4 22. e5 $1 Nh5 23. Bxf7+ Qxf7 24.
Qxf7+ Kxf7 25. Rd7+ $18) (19... Rf8 {is not any better.} 20. Bxf4 exf4 21. e5
Rxe5 22. Rxe5 Qxe5 23. Nxf7 $18) 20. axb5 axb5 21. Qxb5 h6 22. Bxf4 exf4 23.
Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 24. e5 Ba6 25. Bxf7+ Qxf7 26. Qxc5 Ne8 27. e6 $18 {and White
obtained a winning position.} Qc7 28. Qxc7 Nxc7 29. Rd7 Ne8 30. Ra1 Bf6 31. Ra3
Be5 32. Nd2 Nf6 33. Rf7 Bd6 34. Rxf6 Bxa3 35. bxa3 Bd3 36. Rxf4 Bf5 37. e7 Re8
38. g4 Bd7 39. Rf8+ Rxf8 40. exf8=Q+ Kxf8 41. Kg2 Ke7 42. Kg3 Kd6 43. Kf4 Kd5
44. h4 Ba4 45. Nf3 Bc2 46. g5 h5 47. Ke3 Bb1 48. c4+ Kc5 49. Ne5 Bf5 50. f4 Bb1
51. Kd2 Kd4 52. a4 Ke4 53. Nxg6 Kf5 54. Ne7+ Kg4 55. g6 Kxh4 56. f5 Ba2 57. Kc3
1-0

