{[%evp 0,73,27,29,14,12,49,40,40,39,66,38,47,24,31,19,4,4,4,4,5,-11,-4,-11,16,
11,19,19,28,20,48,31,56,45,47,58,61,45,52,30,25,4,17,4,10,-16,-12,-11,-16,-17,
-20,-15,5,-11,12,0,8,-26,-28,-27,6,-20,24,0,26,146,229,254,262,271,271,313,438,
1135,1135,1135] This game is a good example of what happens if Black
surrenders control of the centre to White.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 b6 {Obviously a
different move order than usual, but it will eventually transpose into one of
the main lines of the g6-London system.} 3. e3 Bb7 4. Nf3 g6 5. Nbd2 d6 {
When Black plays this move, it usually means that he is ready to chase our
bishop with Nh5, so it makes sense to play} 6. h3 {to preserve it from an
exchange.} Bg7 7. Be2 (7. Bd3 {is a better choice, though, preparing e3-e4 in
one go. We have seen this idea at work in game 3.}) 7... Nbd7 8. O-O O-O 9. c3
c5 10. Bh2 (10. Bd3 {is a typical mistake due to} e5 {[%cal Re5e4]}) 10... a6
11. a4 {Not only to prevent b5 but also to highlight the weakness of a6-pawn.
This is an interesting moment. Black has two sensible options.} Ra7 {The plan
is to increase control over e4-square with 12...Qa8, sometimes followed by ...
Rc8, Rac7, etc.} ({In my view} 11... Qc7 {this is more natural than 11...Ra7.}
12. Bd3 {[%cal Rd1e2,Re3e4] White loses a tempo, but this is insignificant
because e3-e4 is White's strongest plan anyway.} (12. Qb3 {is the main move in
the database, but I don't like it too much.}) {Black usually plays} 12... e5 (
12... Rfe8 {allows White to go} 13. e4 e5 14. dxe5 dxe5 (14... Nxe5 15. Nxe5
dxe5 16. Qe2 Nh5 17. Rfd1 Nf4 18. Bxf4 exf4 19. Bc4 Re7 20. Qf3 Rae8 21. Bd5
$14) 15. Re1 Nh5 16. b4 (16. Bf1 $5 Nf4 (16... Bc6 17. Qb3 Nf8 18. Nc4 Rab8 19.
Ne3 $14 {[%cal Re3d5,Rf1a6]}) 17. Nc4 {[%cal Rc4d6]}) 16... Nf4 17. Bf1 {
[%cal Rd1b3]} cxb4 18. cxb4 Rad8 19. Qb3 Nf8 20. Rac1 Qb8 21. Nc4 $14) 13. dxe5
dxe5 (13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Qe2 Rfe8 16. Rfd1 Re7 17. f3 $14 {[%csl Ra6,
Rc7,Re5] and White is slightly better due to the weakened light squares in the
centre.}) 14. Qb3 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rh2c7] In this pawn structure White should
better keep his pawn on e3. Black is never threatening ...e5-e4 because the
pawn is pinned, so there is no need to push the e-pawn, which could become
vulnerable on e4. Moreover, the weakest square in black position is d6, so
White has an easy plan: Nc4, Rfd1, and bishop back.} Rfe8 15. Rfd1 {[%csl Rb6,
Rd6]} h6 {prevents Ng5 ideas (as in Le-Nakamura game), but it creates a new
weakness on g6.} (15... Qc8 {Black moves the queen away to unpin and threaten
a fork on e4, but this runs into} 16. Nc4 {[%cal Rc4d6] and things are not
looking good for Black.}) {Therefore, White plays} 16. Nh4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal
Rh4g6]} Nf8 17. Nc4 N6d7 18. Bf1 {[%csl Rd6]} Re6 19. Rd2 {[%cal Ra1d1] White
simply doubles up on the d-file, with a clear advantage.}) 12. Qb1 {An
interesting idea, used by Ivanchuk as well. White simply wants to overprotect
the e4-square, stopping Ne4 and supporting e3-e4 at the same time. Moreover,
the queen sometimes supports b2-b4 break, as well. Qc2 is a worse version of
this idea due to the problems along the c-file after Rc8.} Qa8 13. Bd3 Rc8 (
13... cxd4 {is maybe the best try for Black, though. After} 14. cxd4 (14. exd4
{is another option, but Black has a strong tactical idea} Bh6 $1) 14... Nd5 {
Black is aiming to take control of b4-square.} 15. e4 Nb4 16. Bf4 Rc8 17. Ra3
Nxd3 18. Qxd3 a5 19. Re1 Ba6 20. Qe3 Rc2 {This looks pretty good for Black on
the surface, but White has a way to keep some initiative with} 21. e5 $1 dxe5
22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. dxe5 Rxb2 24. e6 f6 25. Rb3 Rxb3 26. Nxb3 {and the black
bishop is pretty poorly placed on g7.}) 14. Re1 Ne8 {Black employs a rather
passive strategy in anticipation of 15.e4.} 15. e4 e6 16. Qd1 {The queen has
fulfilled its purpose on b1, so now we recentralize it.} Bc6 17. Qe2 $14 {
White has everything under control and meanwhile Black is struggling to find a
plan.} d5 {This was not a good idea. White will have an easy kingside attack
now.} 18. e5 $16 c4 19. Bc2 {This is one of those positions where the engine
is a bit useless. For some reason, I found that the computer always likes the
black position while I think that White is strategically winning. It should be
a matter of time before White launches a winning kingside attack, for example:
Bf4-Qe3-h4-h5-g3-Kg2-Rh1} b5 20. a5 {It is important to block the queenside.}
b4 21. Bf4 Rb8 22. Qe3 bxc3 23. bxc3 Rb2 24. Rec1 Nc7 25. Nf1 Nb5 {Black's
counterplay is insufficient.} 26. N1h2 Qf8 27. Ba4 (27. Ng4 {was even quicker}
h5 28. Nh6+ Kh8 29. g4 {[%cal Rg1g2,Rc1h1] with a winning attack.}) 27... Rb7
28. h4 h5 29. Ng5 Nb8 30. g4 {It is all over now.} Na3 31. Bd1 hxg4 32. Nxg4
Nd7 33. Qh3 Qe7 34. h5 gxh5 35. Qxh5 f6 36. Qh7+ Kf8 37. Nh6 1-0

