{[%evp 0,74,32,23,18,24,44,47,47,41,40,24,25,16,35,-31,17,12,12,10,1,7,11,28,
45,25,53,15,47,6,18,17,66,43,55,57,24,41,69,82,118,94,200,119,94,136,136,117,
190,147,147,147,245,245,320,229,258,208,237,311,426,335,297,210,340,340,365,
425,431,425,435,435,566,569,568,573,584]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3
O-O {This is the move order where Black postpones d6-move.} 5. Be2 {This way,
White keeps an option of pushing c2-c4 in some situations.} ({Alternatives are
} 5. c3 d6 (5... d5) 6. h3) ({and} 5. h3 d6 6. c3) 5... d6 6. h3 {This move
order is quite flexible if Black play either Nc6(Nfd7), e5 or the plan with
the double fianchetto and c5. However, I find it less accurate for White than
6.c3 because of 6...c5 possibility.} (6. c3 $142) 6... Nc6 (6... c5 $142) 7.
Bh2 {Whenever Black is ready for the e5-break, Bh2 makes perfect sense.} Nd7 8.
O-O e5 {One of the benefits of postponing c2-c3 is that we are flexible with
our choice of plan. In this game, Grachev chose} 9. c4 (9. c3 {is also
possible. The London system specialist Gata Kamsky has played plenty of games
in this structure.}) {Black has an important decision to make.} 9... f5 (9...
exd4 10. exd4 Qf6 {is another option, but it is a very risky try!} 11. Nc3 $1 {
is the point.} Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Nd5 c6 (13... Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Bxb2 15.
Nxc7 Rb8 16. Bxd6 $18) 14. Nc7 Rb8 15. Bxd6 $16) 10. Nc3 e4 11. Nd2 Nf6 {
[%csl Rc7,Rd6,Rh2][%cal Rh2c7] This position resembles a reversed French
Defence with a single (but huge) difference that our Bh2 is a strong bishop,
instead of a bad one on c1. It is not only a strong defensive piece, but it
often becomes an important participant in the queenside attack on d6 and c7
pawns.} 12. Rc1 {This is probably the best way to start preparing our
counterplay on the queenside. White is looking for a way to open up the c-file
by pushing d5-c5-cxd6-Nb5 where both Bh2 and Nb5 will be ideally connected
with Rc1.} Ne7 {The knight moves toward the kingside.} ({The other plan is} 
12... g5 {[%cal Rd8e8,Re8g6] when Black is aggressively trying to set up the
kingside attack. I believe that we should act immediately with} 13. d5 Ne5 {
This is more natural than the alternative.} (13... Ne7 14. Nb3 {[%cal Rc4c5]}
b6 15. Nd4 {[%cal Rd4e6]} Qe8 16. b4 {[%cal Rc3b5,Rd4e6,Rc4c5]}) {Here White
has an interesting decision to transform his advantage:} 14. Bxe5 $5 dxe5 15.
c5 {White creates a pawn majority on the queenside. Meanwhile, it is difficult
for Black to push f5-f4 and his dark-squared bishop is very passive.} Kh8 16.
Qb3 {[%csl Re4]} Qe8 (16... h5 {leads to some major complications which
eventually work out for White.} 17. Rcd1 g4 18. hxg4 hxg4 19. g3 f4 (19... Nh7
20. Kg2 Ng5 21. Rh1+ Kg8 (21... Nh3 22. Rh2) 22. d6+) 20. exf4 exf4 21. Ndxe4
Qe8 (21... f3 {is an all-in attempt, but White should be winning after} 22. Bb5
a6 23. Ba4 {[%cal Rd5d6]}) 22. Ng5 $1 f3 {[#] White has a strong reply here}
23. Rfe1 $1 {[%cal Re2f1]} fxe2 24. Nxe2 {[%cal Re2f4] The knight is coming to
f4, stopping black attack.} Qh5 25. Ne6 Bxe6 26. dxe6 {[%cal Re2f4]} Bh6 27. e7
Rfe8 28. Nc3 Kg7 29. Nd5 $18) 17. Nb5 Nxd5 (17... Qf7 18. d6) 18. Qxd5 c6 19.
Qb3 cxb5 20. Qxb5 {[%cal Rd2c4,Rc4d6] White has a clear positional advantage,
intending to reroute the knight to d6 via c4. Bg7 remains a poor piece.} Bd7 (
20... Qxb5 21. Bxb5 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Rd2c4,Rc4d6,Rf1d1]}) 21. Qxb7 $16) 13. b4
(13. d5 $5 g5 14. b4 Ng6 15. c5 Kh8 16. Nc4 Ne8 17. Qc2) 13... c6 {In my view,
this is not a good move since it provides White with targets for attack.} ({
Black should focus on kingside play with} 13... g5 {Here, White's best choice
is, once again,} 14. d5 {preparing to manoeuvre one of the knights to
d4-square.} Qe8 (14... Kh8 15. Qb3 {[%cal Rc4c5]} Ng6 16. c5 $36 {[%csl Rc7,
Rd6][%cal Rc3b5] and White is simply faster with queenside attack.}) 15. Nb5
$14) 14. a4 Be6 15. a5 d5 {This is too weakening for Black. His pawn chain
will not hold.} (15... a6 {is a better alternative, although it is also not
ideal because it weakens the b6-square. White has a strong sequence now:} 16.
Nb3 Kh8 {[#]} 17. d5 $1 {A crucial move in this structure, clearing d4-square
for the knight.} cxd5 18. c5 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Rd6][%cal Rh2d6] A powerful
mini-combination, allowing the white piece to swarm the queenside. Importantly,
the h2-bishop joins the game with a strong effect.} dxc5 19. Nxc5 Bc8 20. N3a4
{[%csl Ra8,Rh2][%cal Ra4b6] and White completely dominates on the dark-squares.
}) 16. a6 b6 17. b5 {The c6-d5 pawn chain falls apart and Black is left with
multiple weaknesses on the queenside (a7, c7 and d6). White pieces easily
assume attacking positions on the queenside, especially as they are supported
by Bh2. Strategically speaking, the game is practically over.} Rc8 18. bxc6
Nxc6 19. Nb5 Qd7 20. Nd6 Rcd8 21. Nb7 Rc8 22. c5 $1 {Bb5 is coming and White
is about to win material.} bxc5 23. Rxc5 g5 24. Bb5 f4 25. exf4 (25. Na5 $18)
25... gxf4 26. Bxf4 Ng4 27. Bg3 Bxd4 28. Rxc6 Rxc6 29. hxg4 Bb6 30. Nb3 e3 31.
Bxc6 Qxc6 32. Nd4 e2 33. Nxc6 exd1=R 34. Rxd1 Bxg4 35. Rxd5 Be2 36. Rg5+ Kf7
37. Rf5+ Ke8 1-0

