1. d4 d6 2. Bf4 {This move order may not be the most accurate for White when
the black knight is still on g8.} g6 3. h3 Bg7 4. Nf3 Nf6 (4... Nd7 $1 {
This is the reason why. Without the knight on f6, Black easily pushes ...e5
and later develops the knight to h6, etc.} 5. e3 e5 6. Bh2 Nh6 $1 7. Be2 O-O 8.
O-O f5 $132) 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 Nfd7 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Re7e5,Rf7f5]} 7. Bh2 e5 8.
c4 Nc6 9. Nc3 {This move order seems a bit more accurate than Grachev's game
against Karjakin because Nc3 is slightly more useful than 0-0 at this stage.}
exd4 {Not such a popular approach, but a reasonable one, opening the diagonal
for the dark-squared bishop.} ({We have already checked} 9... f5 10. O-O e4 11.
Nd2 Nf6 12. Rc1 {in the previous example.}) 10. exd4 Nf6 ({The point is that} 
10... Qf6 {runs into} 11. Nd5 {and this would not have been possible if White
had castled on move 9.}) 11. O-O Re8 {An interesting moment. White needs to
choose a plan. Grachev played a flexible move} 12. Re1 {This way, White is
well-prepared for a possible ...d5-break.} ({On the other hand, the
natural-looking} 12. Bd3 {[%csl Re4,Rf5] stops Black's counterplay with Bf5
and Ne4, but then} d5 {is stronger for Black than after 12.Re1} (12... Bd7 13.
Qd2 $14 {[%cal Rf1e1,Ra2a3,Rb2b4] gives White easier play due to the extra
space.}) {Now, the d4-pawn is vulnerable and White needs to close the centre
with} 13. c5 {Naturally, Black activates his pieces with} Ne4 14. Re1 Bf5 {
but White has an interesting idea} 15. Bb5 {giving up the bishop for the
knight in order to take control over the important e5-square.} a6 16. Bxc6 bxc6
17. Ne5 {[%cal Re5c6]} Bxe5 18. dxe5 Nxc5 {[%csl Rf6,Rg5,Rg7,Rg8,Rh6] Black
has won a pawn, but the primary positional factor in this position is the
weakness of dark squares around the king. Therefore, I prefer the white
position - for example:} 19. Na4 Nxa4 (19... Ne6 20. g4 $18 {traps the bishop.}
) 20. Qxa4 c5 (20... Bd7 21. Qd4 {[%csl Rc5,Re5][%cal Ra1c1] establishes the
blockade on the dark squares.}) 21. Qa5 c4 22. e6 $1 {We finally bring the
dark-squared bishop into the game.} Rxe6 23. Bxc7 {and White keeps very good
attacking chances on the dark squares. A plan like Be5-d4, followed by queen
transfer to the kingside seems very unpleasant for Black.}) 12... Bf5 ({
Here, the move} 12... d5 {is not as good as in the previous variation because
White can stabilize the centre with} 13. b3 $14 {[%csl Rd4]}) 13. d5 {White
takes an opportunity to seize space in the centre and centralize his knight
with a tempo.} Nb4 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. a3 Na6 16. Bf3 {It is crucial to take
control over e4-square in order to limit the opponent's counterplay.} (16. b4 {
allows} Ne4 $132) 16... Rxe1+ 17. Qxe1 Nc5 18. Qd1 {This is the safest move,
keeping control over some important squares on the queenside.} ({However,} 18.
b4 {might be an improvement. For example:} Na4 (18... Ne8 $5 19. Rd1 Na4 20.
Nxa4 Bxa4 21. Rd3 Nf6 22. c5) 19. Bf4 Nxc3 20. Qxc3) 18... a5 ({Black would
have obtained good counterplay with} 18... Qe7 $1 19. b4 Nfe4 $1) 19. b4 $6
axb4 20. axb4 Rxa1 21. Qxa1 Nd3 22. Qb1 {[#] This was the critical moment for
Black. Here, he missed an opportunity to take the initiative.} Ne5 $2 ({
A simple} 22... Qe7 $1 23. Nde2 (23. Qxd3 Qe1+ 24. Qf1 Qxc3) 23... Ne5 $15) ({
or complicated} 22... Nxf2 $5 23. Nce2 (23. Kxf2 Ng4+ 24. hxg4 Bxd4+ 25. Kf1
Bxc3 $19) 23... Nxh3+ $1 24. gxh3 Bxh3 $15 {would have been better choices
than a relatively passive game continuation.}) 23. Be2 $14 {White has a slight
edge thanks to his space advantage, although this is difficult to convert into
something more tangible against Black's best play.} Bc8 24. Bf1 Ne8 25. Ncb5 c6
26. dxc6 bxc6 $4 {This was a decisive blunder.} (26... Nxc6 $14) 27. Bxe5 dxe5
28. Nxc6 Qd7 29. Nba7 Bb7 30. b5 f5 31. c5 e4 32. Nb8 Qd4 33. c6 Qxa7 34. Qb3+
Kh8 35. Nd7 Bd4 36. Qf7 Bxf2+ 37. Kh1 Ng7 38. Qf8# 1-0

