1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. h3 d6 5. c3 {Obviously I have chosen the move
c3 to prepare against c5. But I would also like to draw your attention to the
fact that I postponed the development of my knight to f3. The reason behind it
was to play Ne2 if Black pushes ...e5-e4 too early. This is a rare move order
that I have come up with myself, and it can be effective sometimes (see 6...
Nfd7).} O-O 6. Bh2 Nbd7 ({In case of} 6... Nfd7 7. Nd2 e5 8. Bd3 f5 {I would
play} 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. O-O {and if} e4 11. Bc2 Nf6 12. c4 {the knight is
transferred to c3-square.}) 7. Nf3 {I thought that my opponent would play the
system with ... c5 and ...b6, but he chose a different plan} e6 {During the
game I had thought that this move was just bad, but, actually, it makes sense.
Black is trying to play Qe7 instead of the passive Qe8.} 8. Bd3 $5 Qe7 9. O-O
e5 10. Be2 {The first impression is that we have lost a tempo, but if you
think about it, Black also did the same by playing with his e-pawn twice. So,
we are basically back to a normal position.} e4 {I don't really believe in
this move. White definitely obtains easier play in this structure. His
queenside play after Nfd2,c4,Nc3, etc. unfolds naturally, while Black has a
much more difficult time creating something on the kingside.} ({I believe that
Black should preserve their flexibility with} 10... b6 {Here, I like the idea
of Gata Kamsky:} 11. a4 a5 12. Na3 {This way, we not only secure d2-square for
the other knight, but also get ready to put pressure on c7-pawn with Nb5.} Bb7
13. Nb5 Rac8 (13... c6 {meets a tactical refutation} 14. Nxd6 $1 Qxd6 15. dxe5
Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 Nd5 17. c4 {and White wins a pawn.}) 14. Nd2 h5 {This is the
most flexible option for Black.} (14... e4 15. b4 $36 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Rd2b3]
and White can put pressure on the a5-pawn with Nb3 next.}) {Here is a sample
line:} 15. Re1 Rfe8 16. Qc2 c6 17. Na3 {[%cal Ra3c4]} d5 {[%csl Rb7]} 18. Qb3
Qd8 19. Bf1 e4 (19... exd4 20. exd4 {[%csl Rb7,Rf1,Rg7,Rh2]}) 20. c4 $14) 11.
Nfd2 h5 12. c4 Re8 13. Nc3 Nf8 {After the centre has been closed, we have
standard play for both Black and White.} 14. Rc1 c6 15. b4 Bf5 16. Nb3 {
We have already analyzed this manoeuvre in one of the previous games. White
prepares clearance of d4-square with 17.d5, followed by 18.c5.} Qd7 {Black
prepares a sacrifice on h3.} ({In case of something slower like} 16... N8h7 {
White has two good options:} 17. b5 ({and} 17. d5 cxd5 18. c5 dxc5 19. bxc5 Ng5
20. Bd6 Qd7 21. h4 {It is crucial to prevent a sacrifice on h3.} Ne6 22. Bb5
$18) 17... Ng5 18. c5 d5 19. Na5 Qd7 20. h4 Ne6 21. bxc6 bxc6 22. Qa4 Nd8 23.
Rb1 $16) 17. d5 Rad8 ({My plan was to answer} 17... cxd5 {with} 18. c5 $1 {
[%csl Rd6][%cal Re2b5,Rb5e8] and Black is already in trouble.} Bxh3 19. cxd6 {
[%cal Rb3c5]} Bg4 20. Nxd5 Bxe2 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. Qxe2 {[%cal Rb3c5]}) 18.
dxc6 bxc6 19. c5 d5 (19... dxc5 20. Nxc5 Qe7 21. Qa4) 20. b5 {White is
strategically winning since he will get a strong passed pawn on the c-file and
black has no attack to speak of. The h2-bishop becomes a monster once the
diagonal has cleared up.} Bxh3 {Sometimes it is better to try a desperate idea
to muddy the waters than to defend passively. However, here Black cannot
generate enough compensation for the piece even with best play.} 21. bxc6 Qf5
22. gxh3 Qxh3 23. c7 Rd7 (23... Rc8 24. Nxd5) 24. Nd4 {I decided to keep my
pieces closer to the king to defend against the kingside attack.} (24. c6 {
was even stronger, though.} Rde7 25. Kh1 Rxc7 26. Nb5 Rce7 27. Rg1) 24... N8h7
25. Kh1 Ng4 26. Bxg4 hxg4 27. Rg1 {The rook joins defence.} Be5 (27... Nf6 28.
Ncb5 {[%cal Rb5d6]}) (27... f5 28. c6 Rxc7 29. Nxd5) 28. Rg2 f5 29. c6 Rf7 30.
Nxd5 Ng5 31. Nf4 {There were many winning possibilities here, but I wanted to
make sure to exchange Black's attackers.} Bxf4 32. exf4 Nf3 33. Nxf3 exf3 34.
Rg3 Qh8 35. Qd7 $1 {I hoped that my opponent would take the queen, which would
have made it a really nice picture.} Rff8 36. Qd5+ Kh7 37. Rb1 Qc3 38. Rgg1 Rc8
39. Qd7+ Kh6 40. Rbe1 Qb2 41. Re7 Rh8 {[#] Here, White has a nice win with} 42.
Bg3 $1 {[%cal Rg3h4,Rh4g5,Re7h7] threatening to checkmate with Bh4-g5 and Rh7
with checkmate} Qf6 43. Rf7 Rxc7 44. Qxc7 1-0

