{[%evp 0,59,21,21,21,29,38,44,36,30,33,30,29,8,29,-17,44,15,22,-15,20,-19,-17,
-47,-46,-38,32,43,50,48,90,80,80,4,40,62,91,94,98,106,123,51,183,202,202,150,
238,198,215,137,193,193,262,278,271,286,342,342,369,470,470,526]} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be2 Nc6 7. O-O Nd7 8. Bh2 e5 9. c3 {
This game is an example of White's strategy with the pawn on c3 instead of c4.}
f5 10. a4 {Grabbing more space in search for an alternative development for
the Nb1 - sometimes it can go to a3.} Kh8 11. b4 e4 (11... g5 12. a5 Qf6 13.
Na3 a6 14. b5 Nxa5 15. bxa6 b6 16. Nb5 c6 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Nd6 Bxa6 19. Bxa6
Rxa6 20. Nc4 Qe7 21. Nxg5 Nc5 22. Qh5 h6 23. Nxe5 Qxg5 24. Nf7+ Rxf7 25. Qxf7)
12. Nfd2 d5 $6 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rh2c7] A huge positional mistake. Now Bh2 is a
monster bishop.} (12... a5 13. b5 Ne7 14. c4 b6 15. Nc3 Nf6 16. c5) (12... g5 {
should be the critical line for the variation.} 13. b5 Ne7 14. c4 Nf6 15. Nc3
Ng6 16. a5 Qe7 {[%cal Rf5f4]} 17. Qc2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rc2e4]} Bd7 18. b6 c6 (
18... axb6 19. axb6 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 c6 21. Ra5 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Ra5g5]} h6 22. g4
{[%csl Re4]}) 19. a6) 13. b5 Ne7 14. c4 c6 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Nc3
Nf6 18. Nb5 {[%csl Rc7,Rd6] A dream scenario for us. The rest should be easy.}
a6 19. Nd6 Be6 20. Nb3 g5 21. Nc5 Bg8 22. Be5 (22. Rb1 Ra7 23. a5 {[%cal Rb1b6]
} Qxa5 24. Ndb7 Qa2 25. Bd6) 22... f4 23. exf4 gxf4 24. Bxf4 Ng6 25. Bg3 Qe7
26. Nf5 Qf7 27. Rb1 Nd7 28. Nd6 Qe7 29. Rb7 Rad8 30. Bg4 1-0

